# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: electromagnetism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The law states that the magnitude, or absolute value, of the attractive or repulsive electrostatic force between two point charges is directly proportional to the product of the magnitudes of their charges and inversely proportional to the square of the distance between them.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Here, *k*e is the **Coulomb constant**, *q*1 and *q*2 are the quantities of each charge, and the scalar *r* is the distance between the charges.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The force is along the straight line joining the two bodies.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] If the charges have the same sign, the electrostatic force between them makes them repel; if they have different signs, the force between them makes them attract.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Being an inverse-square law, the law is similar to Isaac Newton's inverse-square law of universal gravitation, but gravitational forces always make things attract, while electrostatic forces make charges attract or repel.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Also, gravitational forces are much weaker than electrostatic forces.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Coulomb's law can be used to derive Gauss's law, and vice versa.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] In the case of a single point charge at rest, the two laws are equivalent, expressing the same physical law in different ways.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The law has been tested extensively, and observations have upheld the law on the scale from 10−16 m to 108 m.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The time-dependent generalization of Coulomb's law is given by Jefimenko's equations, which describe the electric field and magnetic fields generated by time-dependent distributions of electric charge and current.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Ancient cultures around the Mediterranean knew that certain objects, such as rods of amber, could be rubbed with cat's fur to attract light objects like feathers and pieces of paper.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Thales of Miletus made the first recorded description of static electricity around 600 BC, when he noticed that friction could make a piece of amber attract small objects.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] In 1600, English scientist William Gilbert made a careful study of electricity and magnetism, distinguishing the lodestone effect from static electricity produced by rubbing amber.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] He coined the Neo-Latin word *electricus* ("of amber" or "like amber", from ἤλεκτρον [*elektron*], the Greek word for "amber") to refer to the property of attracting small objects after being rubbed.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] This association gave rise to the English words "electric" and "electricity", which made their first appearance in print in Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica* of 1646.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Based on experiments with electrically charged spheres, Joseph Priestley of England was among the first to propose that electrical force followed an inverse-square law, similar to Newton's law of universal gravitation.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] However, he did not generalize or elaborate on this.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] In 1767, he conjectured that the force between charges varied as the inverse square of the distance.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] In 1769, Scottish physicist John Robison announced that, according to his measurements, the force of repulsion between two spheres with charges of the same sign varied as *x*−2.06.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] In the early 1770s, the dependence of the force between charged bodies upon both distance and charge had already been discovered, but not published, by Henry Cavendish of England.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Finally, in 1785, the French physicist Charles-Augustin de Coulomb published his first three reports of electricity and magnetism where he stated his law.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] This publication was essential to the development of the theory of electromagnetism.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] He used a torsion balance to study the repulsion and attraction forces of charged particles, and determined that the magnitude of the electric force between two point charges is directly proportional to the product of the charges and inversely proportional to the square of the distance between them.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The torsion balance consists of a bar suspended from its middle by a thin fiber.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The fiber acts as a very weak torsion spring.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] In Coulomb's experiment, the torsion balance was an insulating rod with a metal-coated ball attached to one end, suspended by a silk thread.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The ball was charged with a known charge of static electricity, and a second charged ball of the same polarity was brought near it.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The two charged balls repelled one another, twisting the fiber through a certain angle, which could be read from a scale on the instrument.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] By knowing how much force it took to twist the fiber through a given angle, Coulomb was able to calculate the force between the balls and derive his inverse-square proportionality law.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] where ${\textstyle \mathbf {r_{12}=r_{1}-r_{2}} }$ is the displacement vector between the charges, ${\textstyle {\hat {\mathbf {r} }}_{12}}$ a unit vector pointing from ${\textstyle q_{2}}$ to ${\textstyle q_{1}}$ , and $\varepsilon _{0}$ the electric constant.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Here, ${\textstyle \mathbf {\hat {r}} _{12}}$ is used for the vector notation.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The electrostatic force ${\textstyle \mathbf {F} _{2}}$ experienced by $q_{2}$ , according to Newton's third law, is ${\textstyle \mathbf {F} _{2}=-\mathbf {F} _{1}}$ .
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] If both charges have the same sign (like charges) then the product $q_{1}q_{2}$ is positive and the direction of the force on $q_{1}$ is given by ${\textstyle {\widehat {\mathbf {r} }}_{12}}$ ; the charges repel each other.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] If the charges have opposite signs then the product $q_{1}q_{2}$ is negative and the direction of the force on $q_{1}$ is ${\textstyle -{\hat {\mathbf {r} }}_{12}}$ ; the charges attract each other.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The law of superposition allows Coulomb's law to be extended to include any number of point charges.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The force acting on a point charge due to a system of point charges is simply the vector addition of the individual forces acting alone on that point charge due to each one of the charges.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The resulting force vector is parallel to the electric field vector at that point, with that point charge removed.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] where $q_{i}$ is the magnitude of the *i* th charge, ${\textstyle \mathbf {r} _{i}}$ is the vector from its position to $\mathbf {r}$ and ${\textstyle {\hat {\mathbf {r} }}_{i}}$ is the unit vector in the direction of $\mathbf {r} _{i}$ .
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] In this case, the principle of linear superposition is also used.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] For a continuous charge distribution, an integral over the region containing the charge is equivalent to an infinite summation, treating each infinitesimal element of space as a point charge $dq$ .
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The distribution of charge is usually linear, surface or volumetric.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Charge is always discrete in reality, and the "continuous charge" assumption is just an approximation that is not supposed to allow $|\mathbf {r} -\mathbf {r'} |=0$ to be analyzed.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The constant $\varepsilon _{0}$ is the vacuum electric permittivity.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The charges must not overlap (e.g. they must be distinct point charges).
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The charges must be stationary with respect to a non-accelerating frame of reference.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The last of these is known as the electrostatic approximation.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] When movement takes place, an extra factor is introduced, which alters the force produced on the two objects.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] This extra part of the force is called the magnetic force.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] For slow movement, the magnetic force is minimal and Coulomb's law can still be considered approximately correct.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] A more accurate approximation in this case is, however, the Weber force.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] When the charges are moving more quickly in relation to each other or accelerations occur, Maxwell's equations and Einstein's theory of relativity must be taken into consideration.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] An electric field is a vector field that associates to each point in space the Coulomb force experienced by a unit test charge.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The strength and direction of the Coulomb force ${\textstyle \mathbf {F} }$ on a charge ${\textstyle q_{t}}$ depends on the electric field ${\textstyle \mathbf {E} }$ established by other charges that it finds itself in, such that ${\textstyle \mathbf {F} =q_{t}\mathbf {E} }$ .
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] In the simplest case, the field is considered to be generated solely by a single source point charge.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] More generally, the field can be generated by a distribution of charges who contribute to the overall by the principle of superposition.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] If the field is generated by a positive source point charge ${\textstyle q}$ , the direction of the electric field points along lines directed radially outwards from it, i.e. in the direction that a positive point test charge ${\textstyle q_{t}}$ would move if placed in the field.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] For a negative point source charge, the direction is radially inwards.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The magnitude of the electric field **E** can be derived from Coulomb's law.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Coulomb's law holds even within atoms, correctly describing the force between the positively charged atomic nucleus and each of the negatively charged electrons.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] This simple law also correctly accounts for the forces that bind atoms together to form molecules and for the forces that bind atoms and molecules together to form solids and liquids.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Generally, as the distance between ions increases, the force of attraction, and binding energy, approach zero and ionic bonding is less favorable.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] As the magnitude of opposing charges increases, energy increases and ionic bonding is more favorable.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Strictly speaking, Gauss's law cannot be derived from Coulomb's law alone, since Coulomb's law gives the electric field due to an individual, electrostatic point charge only.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] However, Gauss's law *can* be proven from Coulomb's law if it is assumed, in addition, that the electric field obeys the superposition principle.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The superposition principle states that the resulting field is the vector sum of fields generated by each particle (or the integral, if the charges are distributed smoothly in space).
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Using the "sifting property" of the Dirac delta function, we arrive at $\nabla \cdot \mathbf {E} (\mathbf {r} )={\frac {\rho (\mathbf {r} )}{\varepsilon _{0}}},$ which is the differential form of Gauss's law, as desired.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Since Coulomb's law only applies to stationary charges, there is no reason to expect Gauss's law to hold for moving charges based on this derivation alone.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] In fact, Gauss's law does hold for moving charges, and, in this respect, Gauss's law is more general than Coulomb's law.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] It is true for all $\mathbf {r} \neq \mathbf {r'}$ that $\nabla _{\mathbf {r} }\cdot \mathbf {e} (\mathbf {r,r'} )=0$ .
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Consider now a compact set $V\subseteq R^{3}$ having a piecewise smooth boundary $\partial V$ such that $\Omega \cap V=\emptyset$ .
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Therefore the flux through a closed surface generated by some charge density outside (the surface) is null.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Now consider $\mathbf {r} _{0}\in \Omega$ , and $B_{R}(\mathbf {r} _{0})\subseteq \Omega$ as the sphere centered in $\mathbf {r} _{0}$ having R as radius (it exists because $\Omega$ is an open set).
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Let $\mathbf {E} _{B_{R}}$ and $\mathbf {E} _{C}$ be the electric field created inside and outside the sphere respectively.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The last equality follows by observing that $(\Omega \setminus B_{R}(\mathbf {r} _{0}))\cap B_{R}(\mathbf {r} _{0})=\emptyset$ , and the argument above.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Where the last equality follows by the mean value theorem for integrals.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Strictly speaking, Coulomb's law cannot be derived from Gauss's law alone, since Gauss's law does not give any information regarding the curl of **E** (see Helmholtz decomposition and Faraday's law).
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] However, Coulomb's law *can* be proven from Gauss's law if it is assumed, in addition, that the electric field from a point charge is spherically symmetric (this assumption, like Coulomb's law itself, is exactly true if the charge is stationary, and approximately true if the charge is in motion).
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] By the assumption of spherical symmetry, the integrand is a constant which can be taken out of the integral.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The result is $4\pi r^{2}{\hat {\mathbf {r} }}\cdot \mathbf {E} (\mathbf {r} )={\frac {Q}{\varepsilon _{0}}}$ where **r̂** is a unit vector pointing radially away from the charge.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Again by spherical symmetry, **E** points in the radial direction, and so we get $\mathbf {E} (\mathbf {r} )={\frac {Q}{4\pi \varepsilon _{0}}}{\frac {\hat {\mathbf {r} }}{r^{2}}}$ which is essentially equivalent to Coulomb's law.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Thus the inverse-square law dependence of the electric field in Coulomb's law follows from Gauss's law.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Coulomb's law can be used to gain insight into the form of the magnetic field generated by moving charges since by special relativity, in certain cases the magnetic field can be shown to be a transformation of forces caused by the electric field.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] When no acceleration is involved in a particle's history, Coulomb's law can be assumed on any test particle in its own inertial frame, supported by symmetry arguments in solving Maxwell's equation, shown above.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Coulomb's law can be expanded to moving test particles to be of the same form.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] This assumption is supported by Lorentz force law which, unlike Coulomb's law is not limited to stationary test charges.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] This form of solutions need not obey Newton's third law as is the case in the framework of special relativity (yet without violating relativistic-energy momentum conservation).
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Note that the expression for electric field reduces to Coulomb's law for non-relativistic speeds of the point charge and that the magnetic field in non-relativistic limit (approximating $\beta \ll 1$ ) can be applied to electric currents to get the Biot–Savart law.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] These solutions, when expressed in retarded time also correspond to the general solution of Maxwell's equations given by solutions of Liénard–Wiechert potential, due to the validity of Coulomb's law within its specific range of application.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Also note that the spherical symmetry for gauss law on stationary charges is not valid for moving charges owing to the breaking of symmetry by the specification of direction of velocity in the problem.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Agreement with Maxwell's equations can also be manually verified for the above two equations.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The **Coulomb potential** admits continuum states (with *E* > 0), describing electron-proton scattering, as well as discrete bound states, representing the hydrogen atom.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] However, the equivalent results of the classical Born derivations for the Coulomb problem are thought to be strictly accidental.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The Coulomb potential, and its derivation, can be seen as a special case of the Yukawa potential, which is the case where the exchanged boson – the photon – has no rest mass.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] It is possible to verify Coulomb's law with a simple experiment.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Consider two small spheres of mass m and same-sign charge q , hanging from two ropes of negligible mass of length l .
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] The forces acting on each sphere are three: the weight $mg$ , the rope tension $\mathbf {T}$ and the electric force $\mathbf {F}$ .
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] If we now discharge one of the spheres, and we put it in contact with the charged sphere, each one of them acquires a charge ${\textstyle {\frac {q}{2}}}$ .
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] Measuring the angles $\theta _{1}$ and $\theta _{2}$ and the distance between the charges $\mathbf {L} _{1}$ and $\mathbf {L} _{2}$ is sufficient to verify that the equality is true taking into account the experimental error.
[src:electromagnetism/coulomb-s-law] In this way, the verification is limited to measuring the distance between the charges and checking that the division approximates the theoretical value.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] An **electric field** (sometimes called **E-field**) is a physical field that surrounds electrically charged particles such as electrons.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] In classical electromagnetism, the electric field of a single charge (or group of charges) describes their capacity to exert attractive or repulsive forces on another charged object.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Charged particles exert attractive forces on each other when the sign of their charges are opposite, one being positive while the other is negative, and repel each other when the signs of the charges are the same.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Because these forces are exerted mutually, two charges must be present for the forces to take place.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] These forces are described by Coulomb's law, which says that the greater the magnitude of the charges, the greater the force, and the greater the distance between them, the weaker the force.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Informally, the greater the charge of an object, the stronger its electric field.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Similarly, an electric field is stronger nearer charged objects and weaker further away.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Electric fields originate from electric charges and time-varying electric currents.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Electric fields and magnetic fields are both manifestations of the electromagnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Electromagnetism is one of the four fundamental interactions of nature.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Electric fields are important in many areas of physics, and are exploited in electrical technology.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] For example, in atomic physics and chemistry, the interaction in the electric field between the atomic nucleus and electrons is the force that holds these particles together in atoms.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Similarly, the interaction in the electric field between atoms is the force responsible for chemical bonding that result in molecules.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] The electric field is defined as a vector field that associates to each point in space the force per unit of charge exerted on an infinitesimal positive test charge at rest at that point.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] The SI unit for the electric field is the volt per meter (V/m), which is equal to the newton per coulomb (N/C).
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] The electric field is defined at each point in space as the force that would be experienced by an infinitesimally small stationary positive test charge at that point divided by the charge.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] The electric field is defined in terms of force, and force is a vector (i.e. having both magnitude and direction), so it follows that an electric field may be described by a vector field.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] The electric field acts between two charges similarly to the way that the gravitational field acts between two masses, as they both obey an inverse-square law with distance.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] This is the basis for Coulomb's law, which states that, for stationary charges, the electric field varies with the source charge and varies inversely with the square of the distance from the source.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] This means that if the source charge were doubled, the electric field would double, and if you move twice as far away from the source, the field at that point would be only one-quarter its original strength.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] The electric field can be visualized with a set of lines whose direction at each point is the same as those of the field, a concept introduced by Michael Faraday, whose term 'lines of force' is still sometimes used.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] This illustration has the useful property that, when drawn so that each line represents the same amount of flux, the strength of the field is proportional to the density of the lines.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Field lines due to stationary charges have several important properties, including that they always originate from positive charges and terminate at negative charges, they enter all good conductors at right angles, and they never cross or close in on themselves.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] The field lines are a representative concept; the field actually permeates all the intervening space between the lines.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] More or fewer lines may be drawn depending on the precision to which it is desired to represent the field.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] The study of electric fields created by stationary charges is called electrostatics.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Faraday's law describes the relationship between a time-varying magnetic field and the electric field.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] One way of stating Faraday's law is that the curl of the electric field is equal to the negative time derivative of the magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] In the absence of time-varying magnetic field, the electric field is therefore called conservative (i.e. curl-free).
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] This implies there are two kinds of electric fields: electrostatic fields and fields arising from time-varying magnetic fields.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] While the curl-free nature of the static electric field allows for a simpler treatment using electrostatics, time-varying magnetic fields are generally treated as a component of a unified electromagnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] The study of magnetic and electric fields that change over time is called electrodynamics.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Electric fields are caused by electric charges, described by Gauss's law, and time varying magnetic fields, described by Faraday's law of induction.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Together, these laws are enough to define the behavior of the electric field.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] However, since the magnetic field is described as a function of electric field, the equations of both fields are coupled and together form Maxwell's equations that describe both fields as a function of charges and currents.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] In the special case of a steady state (stationary charges and currents), the Maxwell-Faraday inductive effect disappears.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Note that $\varepsilon _{0}$ must be replaced with $\varepsilon$ , permittivity, when charges are in non-empty media.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] When the charges $q_{0}$ and $q_{1}$ have the same sign this force is positive, directed away from the other charge, indicating the particles repel each other.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] When the charges have unlike signs the force is negative, indicating the particles attract.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] This is the *electric field* at point $\mathbf {r} _{0}$ due to the point charge $q_{1}$ ; it is a vector-valued function equal to the Coulomb force per unit charge that a positive point charge would experience at the position $\mathbf {r} _{0}$ .
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Since this formula gives the electric field magnitude and direction at any point $\mathbf {r} _{0}$ in space (except at the location of the charge itself, $\mathbf {r} _{1}$ , where it becomes infinite) it defines a vector field.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] From the above formula it can be seen that the electric field due to a point charge is everywhere directed away from the charge if it is positive, and toward the charge if it is negative, and its magnitude decreases with the inverse square of the distance from the charge.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Due to the linearity of Maxwell's equations, electric fields satisfy the superposition principle, which states that the total electric field, at a point, due to a collection of charges is equal to the vector sum of the electric fields at that point due to the individual charges.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] This principle is useful in calculating the field created by multiple point charges.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] The superposition principle allows for the calculation of the electric field due to a distribution of charge density $\rho (\mathbf {r} )$ .
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] If a system is static, such that magnetic fields are not time-varying, then by Faraday's law, the electric field is curl-free.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] In this case, one can define an electric potential, that is, a function $\varphi$ such that $\mathbf {E} =-\nabla \varphi$ .
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] This is analogous to the gravitational potential.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] The difference between the electric potential at two points in space is called the potential difference (or voltage) between the two points.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] In general, however, the electric field cannot be described independently of the magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Faraday's law of induction can be recovered by taking the curl of that equation $\nabla \times \mathbf {E} =-{\frac {\partial (\nabla \times \mathbf {A} )}{\partial t}}=-{\frac {\partial \mathbf {B} }{\partial t}},$ which justifies, a posteriori, the previous form for **E**.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] The equations of electromagnetism are best described in a continuous description.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] However, charges are sometimes best described as discrete points; for example, some models may describe electrons as point sources where charge density is infinite on an infinitesimal section of space.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] A charge q located at $\mathbf {r} _{0}$ can be described mathematically as a charge density ⁠ $\rho (\mathbf {r} )=q\delta (\mathbf {r} -\mathbf {r} _{0})$ ⁠, where the Dirac delta function (in three dimensions) is used.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Conversely, a charge distribution can be approximated by many small point charges.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Electrostatic fields are electric fields that do not change with time.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Such fields are present when systems of charged matter are stationary, or when electric currents are unchanging.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] In that case, Coulomb's law fully describes the field.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] This suggests similarities between the electric field **E** and the gravitational field **g**, or their associated potentials.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Mass is sometimes called "gravitational charge".
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Electrostatic and gravitational forces both are central, conservative and obey an inverse-square law.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] A uniform field is one in which the electric field is constant at every point.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] It can be approximated by placing two conducting plates parallel to each other and maintaining a voltage (potential difference) between them; it is only an approximation because of boundary effects (near the edge of the planes, the electric field is distorted because the plane does not continue).
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Assuming infinite planes, the magnitude of the electric field *E* is: $E=-{\frac {\Delta V}{d}},$ where Δ*V* is the potential difference between the plates and *d* is the distance separating the plates.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] The negative sign arises as positive charges repel, so a positive charge will experience a force away from the positively charged plate, in the opposite direction to that in which the voltage increases.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] In micro- and nano-applications, for instance in relation to semiconductors, a typical magnitude of an electric field is in the order of 106 V⋅m−1, achieved by applying a voltage of the order of 1 volt between conductors spaced 1 μm apart.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] A convenient way to plot the electric field that works even for complex electric fields is to use field lines.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Here the magnitude and direction of an electric field in a region is represented by a number of non-intersecting curved lines that span the region.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] If plotted correctly, the direction of the electric field at any given point is represented by the direction of nearby lines while the magnitude is represented by the density of the field lines in that region.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] They begin at positive charge (or extend from infinity) and end at negative charge (or extend to infinity).
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Further the number of field lines from a given charge must be proportional to that charge.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Electrostatic fields cannot form closed loops.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] (See the figure for an example of a complex electric field line diagram made for a positive point charge which induces electrical charge on the surfaces of 3 nearby conductors.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Field lines can only approximately represent the electric field in a given region.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] (It takes an infinite number of field lines to represent the electric field perfectly.) Nevertheless, these diagrams are useful at illustrating how the electric field changes over a given region.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Electromagnetic fields are electric and magnetic fields, which may change with time, for instance when charges are in motion.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Both the electric current density and the partial derivative of the electric field with respect to time, contribute to the curl of the magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] In addition, the Maxwell–Faraday equation states $\nabla \times \mathbf {E} =-{\frac {\partial \mathbf {B} }{\partial t}}.$ These represent two of Maxwell's four equations and they intricately link the electric and magnetic fields together, resulting in the electromagnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] The equations represent a set of four coupled multi-dimensional partial differential equations which, when solved for a system, describe the combined behavior of the electromagnetic fields.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] As **E** and **B** fields are coupled, it would be misleading to split this expression into "electric" and "magnetic" contributions.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] In particular, an electrostatic field in any given frame of reference in general transforms into a field with a magnetic component in a relatively moving frame.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Accordingly, decomposing the electromagnetic field into an electric and magnetic component is frame-specific, and similarly for the associated energy.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Since **E** and **P** are defined separately, this equation can be used to define **D**.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] The **E** and **D** fields are related by the permittivity of the material, *ε*.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] For non-linear media, **E** and **D** are not proportional.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Materials can have varying extents of linearity, homogeneity and isotropy.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] The invariance of the form of Maxwell's equations under Lorentz transformation can be used to derive the electric field of a uniformly moving point charge.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] The charge of a particle is considered frame invariant, as supported by experimental evidence.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] However the following equation is only applicable when no acceleration is involved in the particle's history where Coulomb's law can be considered or symmetry arguments can be used for solving Maxwell's equations in a simple manner.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] The above equation reduces to that given by Coulomb's law for non-relativistic speeds of the point charge.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Spherical symmetry is not satisfied due to breaking of symmetry in the problem by specification of direction of velocity for calculation of field.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] To illustrate this, field lines of moving charges are sometimes represented as unequally spaced radial lines which would appear equally spaced in a co-moving reference frame.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Special theory of relativity imposes the principle of locality, that requires cause and effect to be time-like separated events where the causal efficacy does not travel faster than the speed of light.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Maxwell's laws are found to confirm to this view since the general solutions of fields are given in terms of retarded time which indicate that electromagnetic disturbances travel at the speed of light.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Advanced time, which also provides a solution for Maxwell's law are ignored as an unphysical solution.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] For the motion of a charged particle, considering for example the case of a moving particle with the above described electric field coming to an abrupt stop, the electric fields at points far from it do not immediately revert to that classically given for a stationary charge.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] On stopping, the field around the stationary points begin to revert to the expected state and this effect propagates outwards at the speed of light while the electric field lines far away from this will continue to point radially towards an assumed moving charge.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] This virtual particle will never be outside the range of propagation of the disturbance in electromagnetic field, since charged particles are restricted to have speeds slower than that of light, which makes it impossible to construct a Gaussian surface in this region that violates Gauss's law.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Another technical difficulty that supports this is that charged particles travelling faster than or equal to speed of light no longer have a unique retarded time.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Since electric field lines are continuous, an electromagnetic pulse of radiation is generated that connects at the boundary of this disturbance travelling outwards at the speed of light.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] In general, any accelerating point charge radiates electromagnetic waves however, non-radiating acceleration is possible in a systems of charges.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] For arbitrarily moving point charges, propagation of potential fields such as Lorenz gauge fields at the speed of light needs to be accounted for by using Liénard–Wiechert potential.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Since the potentials satisfy Maxwell's equations, the fields derived for point charge also satisfy Maxwell's equations.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] The uniqueness of solution for ${\textstyle {t_{r}}}$ for given t , $\mathbf {r}$ and $r_{s}(t)$ is valid for charged particles moving slower than speed of light.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Electromagnetic radiation of accelerating charges is known to be caused by the acceleration dependent term in the electric field from which relativistic correction for Larmor formula is obtained.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] Since the physical interpretation of this indicates that the electric field at a point is governed by the particle's state at a point of time in the future, it is considered as an unphysical solution and hence neglected.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] However, there have been theories exploring the advanced time solutions of Maxwell's equations, such as Feynman Wheeler absorber theory.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] The above equation, although consistent with that of uniformly moving point charges as well as its non-relativistic limit, are not corrected for quantum-mechanical effects.
[src:electromagnetism/electric-field] In the absence of external fields, spherical conductors exhibit a uniform charge distribution on the surface and hence have the same electric field as that of uniform spherical surface distribution.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] An **electromagnetic field** (also **EM field**) is a physical field, varying in space and time, that represents the electric and magnetic influences generated by and acting upon electric charges.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] The field at any point in space and time can be regarded as a combination of an electric field and a magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Because of the interrelationship between the fields, a disturbance in the electric field can create a disturbance in the magnetic field which in turn affects the electric field, leading to an oscillation that propagates through space, known as an *electromagnetic wave*.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Mathematically, the electromagnetic field is a pair of vector fields consisting of one vector for the electric field and one for the magnetic field at each point in space.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] The vectors may change over time and space in accordance with Maxwell's equations.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] The vectors are subject to the rules of special relativity; different observers may determine different vectors.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] The way in which charges and currents (i.e. streams of charges) interact with the electromagnetic field is described by Maxwell's equations and the Lorentz force law.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Maxwell's equations detail how the electric field converges towards or diverges away from electric charges, how the magnetic field curls around electrical currents, and how changes in the electric and magnetic fields influence each other.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] The Lorentz force law states that a charge subject to an electric field feels a force along the direction of the field, and a charge moving through a magnetic field feels a force that is perpendicular both to the magnetic field and to its direction of motion.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] The electromagnetic field is described by classical electrodynamics, an example of a classical field theory.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] This theory describes many macroscopic physical phenomena accurately.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] However, it was unable to explain the photoelectric effect and atomic absorption spectroscopy, experiments at the atomic scale.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] That required the use of quantum mechanics, specifically the quantization of the electromagnetic field and the development of quantum electrodynamics.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] The empirical investigation of electromagnetism is at least as old as the ancient Greek philosopher, mathematician and scientist Thales of Miletus, who around 600 BCE described his experiments rubbing fur of animals on various materials such as amber creating static electricity.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Michael Faraday visualized this in terms of the charges interacting via the electric field.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] An electric field is produced when the charge is stationary with respect to an observer measuring the properties of the charge, and a magnetic field as well as an electric field are produced when the charge moves, creating an electric current with respect to this observer.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Over time, it was realized that the electric and magnetic fields are better thought of as two parts of a greater whole—the electromagnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] In 1820, Hans Christian Ørsted showed that an electric current can deflect a nearby compass needle, establishing that electricity and magnetism are closely related phenomena.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Faraday then made the seminal observation that time-varying magnetic fields could induce electric currents in 1831.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] In 1861, James Clerk Maxwell synthesized all the work to date on electrical and magnetic phenomena into a single mathematical theory, from which he then deduced that light is an electromagnetic wave.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Maxwell's continuous field theory was very successful until evidence supporting the atomic model of matter emerged.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Beginning in 1877, Hendrik Lorentz developed an atomic model of electromagnetism and in 1897 J.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Thomson completed experiments that defined the electron.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] The Lorentz theory works for free charges in electromagnetic fields, but fails to predict the energy spectrum for bound charges in atoms and molecules.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] For that problem, quantum mechanics is needed, ultimately leading to the theory of quantum electrodynamics.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Practical applications of the new understanding of electromagnetic fields emerged in the late 1800s.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] The electrical generator and motor were invented using only the empirical findings like Faraday's and Ampere's laws combined with practical experience.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] There are different mathematical ways of representing the electromagnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] The first one views the electric and magnetic fields as three-dimensional vector fields.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] These vector fields each have a value defined at every point of space and time and are thus often regarded as functions of the space and time coordinates.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] If only the electric field (**E**) is non-zero, and is constant in time, the field is said to be an electrostatic field.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Similarly, if only the magnetic field (**B**) is non-zero and is constant in time, the field is said to be a magnetostatic field.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] However, if either the electric or magnetic field has a time-dependence, then both fields must be considered together as a coupled electromagnetic field using Maxwell's equations.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] With the advent of special relativity, physical laws became amenable to the formalism of tensors.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Maxwell's equations can be written in tensor form, generally viewed by physicists as a more elegant means of expressing physical laws.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] The behavior of electric and magnetic fields, whether in cases of electrostatics, magnetostatics, or electrodynamics (electromagnetic fields), is governed by Maxwell's equations.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] where $\rho$ is the charge density, which is a function of time and position, $\varepsilon _{0}$ is the vacuum permittivity, $\mu _{0}$ is the vacuum permeability, and **J** is the current density vector, also a function of time and position.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Inside a linear material, Maxwell's equations change by switching the permeability and permittivity of free space with the permeability and permittivity of the linear material in question.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Inside other materials which possess more complex responses to electromagnetic fields, these terms are often represented by complex numbers, or tensors.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] The Lorentz force law governs the interaction of the electromagnetic field with charged matter.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] When a field travels across to different media, the behavior of the field changes according to the properties of the media.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] The Maxwell equations simplify when the charge density at each point in space does not change over time and all electric currents likewise remain constant.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Whether a physical effect is attributable to an electric field or to a magnetic field is dependent upon the observer, in a way that special relativity makes mathematically precise.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] For example, suppose that a laboratory contains a long straight wire that carries an electrical current.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] In the frame of reference where the laboratory is at rest, the wire is motionless and electrically neutral: the current, composed of negatively charged electrons, moves against a background of positively charged ions, and the densities of positive and negative charges cancel each other out.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] A test charge near the wire would feel no electrical force from the wire.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] However, if the test charge is in motion parallel to the current, the situation changes.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] In the rest frame of the test charge, the positive and negative charges in the wire are moving at different speeds, and so the positive and negative charge distributions are Lorentz-contracted by different amounts.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Consequently, the wire has a nonzero net charge density, and the test charge must experience a nonzero electric field and thus a nonzero force.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] In the rest frame of the laboratory, there is no electric field to explain the test charge being pulled towards or pushed away from the wire.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] So, an observer in the laboratory rest frame concludes that a *magnetic* field must be present.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] In general, a situation that one observer describes using only an electric field will be described by an observer in a different inertial frame using a combination of electric and magnetic fields.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Analogously, a phenomenon that one observer describes using only a magnetic field will be, in a relatively moving reference frame, described by a combination of fields.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] The rules for relating the fields required in different reference frames are the Lorentz transformations of the fields.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] The fact that the two field variations can be reproduced just by changing the motion of the observer is further evidence that there is only a single actual field involved which is simply being observed differently.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] The two Maxwell equations, Faraday's Law and the Ampère–Maxwell Law, illustrate a very practical feature of the electromagnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Faraday's Law may be stated roughly as "a changing magnetic field inside a loop creates an electric voltage around the loop".
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] This is the principle behind the electric generator.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Ampere's Law roughly states that "an electrical current around a loop creates a magnetic field through the loop".
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Thus, this law can be applied to generate a magnetic field and run an electric motor.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Maxwell's equations can be combined to derive wave equations.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] The solutions of these equations take the form of an electromagnetic wave.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] James Clerk Maxwell was the first to obtain this relationship by his completion of Maxwell's equations with the addition of a displacement current term to Ampere's circuital law.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] This unified the physical understanding of electricity, magnetism, and light: visible light is but one portion of the full range of electromagnetic waves, the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] An electromagnetic field very far from currents and charges (sources) is called electromagnetic radiation (EMR) since it radiates from the charges and currents in the source.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Such radiation can occur across a wide range of frequencies called the electromagnetic spectrum, including radio waves, microwave, infrared, visible light, ultraviolet light, X-rays, and gamma rays.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] The many commercial applications of these radiations are discussed in the named and linked articles.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] A notable application of visible light is that this type of energy from the Sun powers all life on Earth that either makes or uses oxygen.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] A changing electromagnetic field which is physically close to currents and charges (see near and far field for a definition of "close") will have a dipole characteristic that is dominated by either a changing electric dipole, or a changing magnetic dipole.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] This type of dipole field near sources is called an electromagnetic *near-field*.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Changing *electric* dipole fields, as such, are used commercially as near-fields mainly as a source of dielectric heating.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Otherwise, they appear parasitically around conductors which absorb EMR, and around antennas which have the purpose of generating EMR at greater distances.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Changing *magnetic* dipole fields (i.e., magnetic near-fields) are used commercially for many types of magnetic induction devices.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] These include motors and electrical transformers at low frequencies, and devices such as RFID tags, metal detectors, and MRI scanner coils at higher frequencies.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] The potential effects of electromagnetic fields on human health vary widely depending on the frequency, intensity of the fields, and the length of the exposure.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] Low frequency, low intensity, and short duration exposure to electromagnetic radiation is generally considered safe.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-field] On the other hand, radiation from other parts of the electromagnetic spectrum, such as ultraviolet light and gamma rays, are known to cause significant harm in some circumstances.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Michael Faraday is generally credited with the discovery of induction in 1831, and James Clerk Maxwell mathematically described it as Faraday's law of induction.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Lenz's law describes the direction of the induced field.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Faraday's law was later generalized to become the Maxwell–Faraday equation, one of the four Maxwell equations in his theory of electromagnetism.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Electromagnetic induction has found many applications, including electrical components such as inductors and transformers, and devices such as electric motors and generators.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Electromagnetic induction was discovered by Michael Faraday, published in 1831.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] It was discovered independently by Joseph Henry in 1832.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] In Faraday's first experimental demonstration, on August 29, 1831, he wrapped two wires around opposite sides of an iron ring or "torus" (an arrangement similar to a modern toroidal transformer).
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Based on his understanding of electromagnets, he expected that, when current started to flow in one wire, a sort of wave would travel through the ring and cause some electrical effect on the opposite side.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] He plugged one wire into a galvanometer, and watched it as he connected the other wire to a battery.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] He saw a transient current, which he called a "wave of electricity", when he connected the wire to the battery and another when he disconnected it.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] This induction was due to the change in magnetic flux that occurred when the battery was connected and disconnected.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Within two months, Faraday found several other manifestations of electromagnetic induction.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] For example, he saw transient currents when he quickly slid a bar magnet in and out of a coil of wires, and he generated a steady (DC) current by rotating a copper disk near the bar magnet with a sliding electrical lead ("Faraday's disk").
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Faraday explained electromagnetic induction using a concept he called lines of force.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] However, scientists at the time widely rejected his theoretical ideas, mainly because they were not formulated mathematically.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] An exception was James Clerk Maxwell, who used Faraday's ideas as the basis of his quantitative electromagnetic theory.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] In Maxwell's model, the time varying aspect of electromagnetic induction is expressed as a differential equation, which Oliver Heaviside referred to as Faraday's law even though it is slightly different from Faraday's original formulation and does not describe motional emf.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Heaviside's version (see Maxwell–Faraday equation below) is the form recognized today in the group of equations known as Maxwell's equations.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] In 1834 Heinrich Lenz formulated the law named after him to describe the "flux through the circuit".
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Lenz's law gives the direction of the induced emf and current resulting from electromagnetic induction.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Faraday's law of induction makes use of the magnetic flux ΦB through a region of space enclosed by a wire loop.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] The magnetic flux is defined by a surface integral: $\Phi _{\mathrm {B} }=\int _{\Sigma }\mathbf {B} \cdot d\mathbf {A} \,,$ where *d***A** is an element of the surface Σ enclosed by the wire loop, **B** is the magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] The dot product **B**·*d***A** corresponds to an infinitesimal amount of magnetic flux.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] In more visual terms, the magnetic flux through the wire loop is proportional to the number of magnetic field lines that pass through the loop.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] When the flux through the surface changes, Faraday's law of induction says that the wire loop acquires an electromotive force (emf).
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] The direction of the electromotive force is given by Lenz's law which states that an induced current will flow in the direction that will oppose the change which produced it.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] This is due to the negative sign in the previous equation.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] To increase the generated emf, a common approach is to exploit flux linkage by creating a tightly wound coil of wire, composed of *N* identical turns, each with the same magnetic flux going through them.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] In general, the relation between the emf ${\mathcal {E}}$ in a wire loop encircling a surface Σ, and the electric field **E** in the wire is given by ${\mathcal {E}}=\oint _{\partial \Sigma }\mathbf {E} \cdot d{\boldsymbol {\ell }}$ where *d***ℓ** is an element of contour of the surface Σ.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] It is one of the four Maxwell's equations, and therefore plays a fundamental role in the theory of classical electromagnetism.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Faraday's law describes two different phenomena: the *motional emf* generated by a magnetic force on a moving wire (see Lorentz force), and the *transformer emf* that is generated by an electric force due to a changing magnetic field (due to the differential form of the Maxwell–Faraday equation).
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] James Clerk Maxwell drew attention to the separate physical phenomena in 1861.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] This is believed to be a unique example in physics of where such a fundamental law is invoked to explain two such different phenomena.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Albert Einstein noticed that the two situations both corresponded to a relative movement between a conductor and a magnet, and the outcome was unaffected by which one was moving.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] This was one of the principal paths that led him to develop special relativity.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] The emf generated by Faraday's law of induction due to relative movement of a circuit and a magnetic field is the phenomenon underlying electrical generators.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] When a permanent magnet is moved relative to a conductor, or vice versa, an electromotive force is created.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] If the wire is connected through an electrical load, current will flow, and thus electrical energy is generated, converting the mechanical energy of motion to electrical energy.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] For example, the *drum generator* is based upon the figure to the bottom-right.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] A different implementation of this idea is the Faraday's disc, shown in simplified form on the right.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] In the Faraday's disc example, the disc is rotated in a uniform magnetic field perpendicular to the disc, causing a current to flow in the radial arm due to the Lorentz force.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Mechanical work is necessary to drive this current.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] When the generated current flows through the conducting rim, a magnetic field is generated by this current through Ampère's circuital law (labelled "induced B" in the figure).
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] The rim thus becomes an electromagnet that resists rotation of the disc (an example of Lenz's law).
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] On the far side of the figure, the return current flows from the rotating arm through the far side of the rim to the bottom brush.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] The B-field induced by this return current opposes the applied B-field, tending to *decrease* the flux through that side of the circuit, opposing the *increase* in flux due to rotation.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] On the near side of the figure, the return current flows from the rotating arm through the near side of the rim to the bottom brush.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] The induced B-field *increases* the flux on this side of the circuit, opposing the *decrease* in flux due to r the rotation.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] The energy required to keep the disc moving, despite this reactive force, is exactly equal to the electrical energy generated (plus energy wasted due to friction, Joule heating, and other inefficiencies).
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] This behavior is common to all generators converting mechanical energy to electrical energy.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] When the electric current in a loop of wire changes, the changing current creates a changing magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] A second wire in reach of this magnetic field will experience this change in magnetic field as a change in its coupled magnetic flux, ${\frac {d\Phi _{B}}{dt}}$ .
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Therefore, an electromotive force is set up in the second loop called the induced emf or transformer emf.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] If the two ends of this loop are connected through an electrical load, current will flow.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] A current clamp is a type of transformer with a split core which can be spread apart and clipped onto a wire or coil to either measure the current in it or, in reverse, to induce a voltage.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Unlike conventional instruments the clamp does not make electrical contact with the conductor or require it to be disconnected during attachment of the clamp.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Faraday's law is used for measuring the flow of electrically conductive liquids and slurries.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Such instruments are called magnetic flow meters.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] where ℓ is the distance between electrodes in the magnetic flow meter.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Electrical conductors moving through a steady magnetic field, or stationary conductors within a changing magnetic field, will have circular currents induced within them by induction, called eddy currents.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Eddy currents flow in closed loops in planes perpendicular to the magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] They have useful applications in eddy current brakes and induction heating systems.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] However eddy currents induced in the metal magnetic cores of transformers and AC motors and generators are undesirable since they dissipate energy (called core losses) as heat in the resistance of the metal.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Eddy currents consume a considerable amount of energy and often cause a harmful rise in temperature.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Only five laminations or plates are shown in this example, so as to show the subdivision of the eddy currents.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] In practical use, the number of laminations or punchings ranges from 40 to 66 per inch (16 to 26 per centimetre), and brings the eddy current loss down to about one percent.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] While the plates can be separated by insulation, the voltage is so low that the natural rust/oxide coating of the plates is enough to prevent current flow across the laminations.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] This is a rotor approximately 20 mm in diameter from a DC motor used in a CD player.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Note the laminations of the electromagnet pole pieces, used to limit parasitic inductive losses.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] In this illustration, a solid copper bar conductor on a rotating armature is just passing under the tip of the pole piece N of the field magnet.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Note the uneven distribution of the lines of force across the copper bar.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] The magnetic field is more concentrated and thus stronger on the left edge of the copper bar (a,b) while the field is weaker on the right edge (c,d).
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] Since the two edges of the bar move with the same velocity, this difference in field strength across the bar creates whorls or current eddies within the copper bar.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] High current power-frequency devices, such as electric motors, generators and transformers, use multiple small conductors in parallel to break up the eddy flows that can form within large solid conductors.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetic-induction] The same principle is applied to transformers used at higher than power frequency, for example, those used in switch-mode power supplies and the intermediate frequency coupling transformers of radio receivers.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] In physics, **electromagnetism** is an interaction that occurs between particles with electric charge via electromagnetic fields.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] The electromagnetic force is one of the four fundamental forces of nature.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] It is the dominant force in the interactions of atoms and molecules.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Electromagnetism describes and relates the three distinct but closely intertwined phenomena of electricity, magnetism, and optics.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] In, electromagnetism these phenomena are described by the 3 sub-disciplines: electrostatics, magnetostatics, and electrodynamics.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] The electromagnetic force is responsible for many chemical and physical phenomena observed in daily life.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] The electrostatic attraction between atomic nuclei and their electrons holds atoms together.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Electric forces also allow different atoms to combine into molecules.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Meanwhile, magnetic interactions between the spin and angular momentum magnetic moments of electrons also play a role in chemical reactivity; such relationships are studied in spin chemistry.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Electromagnetism has been studied since ancient times to explain the electric phenomena of lightning and static electricity and the magnetic phenomenon of the attraction between magnetized pieces of iron ore and of compasses.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] In the 18th and 19th centuries scientists developed the mathematical relationships between these phenomena and electric charges and currents.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Too they showed that electrical and magnetic phenomena were related and could create a self-sustaining electromagnetic waves which forms visible light and other forms of electromagnetic radiation including Gamma-rays, x-rays, ultraviolet, visible, infrared radiation, microwaves and radio waves.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] In the modern era, scientists continue to refine the theory of electromagnetism to account for the effects of modern physics, including quantum mechanics and relativity.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Quantum electrodynamics (QED) modifies Maxwell's equations to be consistent with the quantized nature of matter.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] In QED, changes in the electromagnetic field are expressed in terms of discrete excitations, particles known as photons, the quanta of light.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Mathematically, electromagnetism is described by electromagnetic fields.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] These are quantities that describe the electrical (electric field) and magnetic (magnetic field) influence at a given location and time.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] The electromagnetic force is the second strongest of the four known fundamental forces and has unlimited range.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] All other forces, known as non-fundamental forces.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] (e.g., friction, contact forces) are derived from the four fundamental forces.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] At high energy, the weak force and electromagnetic force are unified as a single interaction called the electroweak interaction.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Most of the forces involved in interactions between atoms are explained by electromagnetic forces between electrically charged atomic nuclei and electrons.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] The electromagnetic force is also involved in all forms of chemical phenomena.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Electromagnetism explains how materials carry momentum despite being composed of individual particles and empty space.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] The forces we experience when "pushing" or "pulling" ordinary material objects result from intermolecular forces between individual molecules in our bodies and in the objects.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] The effective forces generated by the momentum of electrons' movement is a necessary part of understanding atomic and intermolecular interactions.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] As electrons move between interacting atoms, they carry momentum with them.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] As a collection of electrons becomes more confined, their minimum momentum necessarily increases due to the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] The behavior of matter at the molecular scale, including its density, is determined by the balance between the electromagnetic force and the force generated by the exchange of momentum carried by the electrons themselves.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] The phenomena of electromagnetism is described mathematically using electromagnetic fields.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] An electromagnetic field (also **EM field**) is a physical field, varying in space and time, that represents the electric and magnetic influences generated by and acting upon electric charges.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] There are 6 mathematical quantities which are used to describe electromagnetic fields in 3 distinct cases.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] The electric field, **E**, and magnetic flux density, **B** are used to describe the electromagnetic fields in cases where all the charges are known directly such as the electromagnetic field in a vacuum.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] To describe the case where the charges inside of a material respond to applied electric and magnetic fields, it is useful to define the electric displacement field, **D** and magnetic field strength, **H**, in addition to **E** and **B**.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Finally, it is sometimes useful to describe electromagnetic fields not in terms of force but in terms of potential energy and momentum.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] In this case, the electromagnetic field is represented by the electric potential, V, and the magnetic vector potential, **A**, respectively.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Here, × is the vector cross product, and all quantities in bold are vectors.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] The Lorentz force can be used to define both the electric field **E** and the magnetic flux density **B**.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] When dealing with electromagnetic fields in matter it is often useful to introduce 2 other fields, in addition to **E** and **B**.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Since matter is made of particles with both electric charge and intrinsic magnetic moment it responds to an applied electromagnetic field to produce its own electromagnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] The details are complicated but often can be described by introducing an electric displacement field, **D** to complement **E** and a magnetic field strength, **H**, to complement **E**.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] In advanced formulations of electromagnetism and to simplify certain calculations it is often useful to reformulate the electromagnetic field in terms of electric potential energy and momentum instead of force.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Here, the electromagnetic fields of interest are the electric potential, V, and the magnetic vector potential **A**.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] These are related to **E** and **B** by: ${\begin{aligned}\mathbf {E} &=-\nabla V-{\frac {\partial \mathbf {A} }{\partial t}}\\[1ex]\mathbf {B} &=\nabla \times \mathbf {A} \end{aligned}}$ where ∇ is the gradient, ∇⋅ is the divergence, and ∇× is the curl.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Since classical antiquity, it has been known that some materials, such as amber, attract lightweight particles after rubbing.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] The Greek word *ḗlektron* (ἤλεκτρον), meaning 'amber', was thus the root of the word *electricity*.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Electrostatic phenomena arise from the forces that electric charges exert on each other.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Such forces are described by Coulomb's law.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] In 1600, William Gilbert proposed, in his *De Magnete*, that electricity and magnetism, while both capable of causing attraction and repulsion of objects, were distinct effects.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Mariners had noticed that lightning strikes had the ability to disturb a compass needle.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] The link between lightning and electricity was not confirmed until Benjamin Franklin's proposed experiments in 1752 were conducted on 10 May 1752 by Thomas-François Dalibard of France using a 40-foot-tall (12 m) iron rod instead of a kite and he successfully extracted electrical sparks from a cloud.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] One of the first to discover and publish a link between human-made electric current and magnetism was Gian Romagnosi, who in 1802 noticed that connecting a wire across a voltaic pile deflected a nearby compass needle.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] However, the effect did not become widely known until 1820, when Ørsted performed a similar experiment. Ørsted's work influenced Ampère to conduct further experiments, which eventually gave rise to a new area of physics: electrodynamics.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] By determining a force law for the interaction between elements of electric current, Ampère placed the subject on a solid mathematical foundation.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] In classical electromagnetism, the behavior of the electromagnetic field is described by a set of equations known as Maxwell's equations, and the electromagnetic force is given by the Lorentz force law.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] One of the peculiarities of classical electromagnetism is that it is difficult to reconcile with classical mechanics, but it is compatible with special relativity.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] According to Maxwell's equations, the speed of light in vacuum is a universal constant that is dependent only on the electrical permittivity and magnetic permeability of free space.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] This violates Galilean invariance, a long-standing cornerstone of classical mechanics.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] One way to reconcile the two theories (electromagnetism and classical mechanics) is to assume the existence of a luminiferous aether through which the light propagates.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] However, subsequent experimental efforts failed to detect the presence of the aether.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] After important contributions of Hendrik Lorentz and Henri Poincaré, in 1905, Albert Einstein solved the problem with the introduction of special relativity, which replaced classical kinematics with a new theory of kinematics compatible with classical electromagnetism.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Today few problems in electromagnetism remain unsolved.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] These include: the lack of magnetic monopoles, Abraham–Minkowski controversy, the location in space of the electromagnetic field energy, and the mechanism by which some organisms can sense electric and magnetic fields.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] The Maxwell equations are *linear,* in that a change in the sources (the charges and currents) results in a proportional change of the fields.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Nonlinear dynamics can occur when electromagnetic fields couple to matter that follows nonlinear dynamical laws.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] This is studied, for example, in the subject of magnetohydrodynamics, which combines Maxwell theory with the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Another branch of electromagnetism dealing with nonlinearity is nonlinear optics.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] In the electromagnetic CGS system, electric current is a fundamental quantity defined via Ampère's law and takes the permeability as a dimensionless quantity (relative permeability) whose value in vacuum is unity.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] As a consequence, the square of the speed of light appears explicitly in some of the equations interrelating quantities in this system.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Formulas for physical laws of electromagnetism (such as Maxwell's equations) need to be adjusted depending on what system of units one uses.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] This is because there is no one-to-one correspondence between electromagnetic units in SI and those in CGS, as is the case for mechanical units.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Furthermore, within CGS, there are several plausible choices of electromagnetic units, leading to different unit "sub-systems", including Gaussian, "ESU", "EMU", and Heaviside–Lorentz.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Among these choices, Gaussian units are the most common today, and in fact the phrase "CGS units" is often used to refer specifically to CGS-Gaussian units.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] The theory of electromagnetism is used to understand and design electric circuits, magnetic circuits, and semiconductor devices.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Investigation into electromagnetic phenomena began about 5,000 years ago.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] There is evidence that the ancient Chinese, Mayan, and potentially even Egyptian civilizations knew that the naturally magnetic mineral magnetite had attractive properties, and many incorporated it into their art and architecture.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Ancient people were also aware of lightning and static electricity, although they had no idea of the mechanisms behind these phenomena.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] The Greek philosopher Thales of Miletus discovered around 600 B.C.E. that amber could acquire an electric charge when it was rubbed with cloth, which allowed it to pick up light objects such as pieces of straw.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Thales also experimented with the ability of magnetic rocks to attract one other, and hypothesized that this phenomenon might be connected to the attractive power of amber, foreshadowing the deep connections between electricity and magnetism that would be discovered over 2,000 years later.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Despite all this investigation, ancient civilizations had no understanding of the mathematical basis of electromagnetism, and often analyzed its impacts through the lens of religion rather than science (lightning, for instance, was considered to be a creation of the gods in many cultures).
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Electricity and magnetism were originally considered to be two separate forces.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] This view changed with the publication of James Clerk Maxwell's 1873 *A Treatise on Electricity and Magnetism* in which the interactions of positive and negative charges were shown to be mediated by one force.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Magnetic poles (or states of polarization at individual points) attract or repel one another in a manner similar to positive and negative charges and always exist as pairs: every north pole is yoked to a south pole.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] An electric current inside a wire creates a corresponding circumferential magnetic field outside the wire.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Its direction (clockwise or counter-clockwise) depends on the direction of the current in the wire.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] A current is induced in a loop of wire when it is moved toward or away from a magnetic field, or a magnet is moved towards or away from it; the direction of current depends on that of the movement.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] In April 1820, Hans Christian Ørsted observed that an electrical current in a wire caused a nearby compass needle to move.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] At the time of discovery, Ørsted did not suggest any satisfactory explanation of the phenomenon, nor did he try to represent the phenomenon in a mathematical framework.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] However, three months later he began more intensive investigations.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Soon thereafter he published his findings, proving that an electric current produces a magnetic field as it flows through a wire.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] The CGS unit of magnetic induction (oersted) is named in honor of his contributions to the field of electromagnetism.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] His findings influenced French physicist André-Marie Ampère's developments of a single mathematical form to represent the magnetic forces between current-carrying conductors.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] This unification, which was observed by Michael Faraday, extended by James Clerk Maxwell, and partially reformulated by Oliver Heaviside and Heinrich Hertz, is one of the key accomplishments of 19th-century mathematical physics.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] It has had far-reaching consequences, one of which was the understanding of the nature of light.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Unlike what was proposed by the electromagnetic theory of that time, light and other electromagnetic waves are at present seen as taking the form of quantized, self-propagating oscillatory electromagnetic field disturbances called photons.
[src:electromagnetism/electromagnetism] Different frequencies of oscillation give rise to the different forms of electromagnetic radiation, from radio waves at the lowest frequencies, to visible light at intermediate frequencies, to gamma rays at the highest frequencies.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] In electromagnetism, the **Lorentz force** is the force exerted on a charged particle by electric and magnetic fields.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] It determines how charged particles move in electromagnetic environments and underlies many physical phenomena, from the operation of electric motors and particle accelerators to the behavior of plasmas.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The **electric force** acts in the direction of the electric field for positive charges and opposite to it for negative charges, tending to accelerate the particle in a straight line.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The **magnetic force** is perpendicular to both the particle's velocity and the magnetic field, and it causes the particle to move along a curved trajectory, often circular or helical in form, depending on the directions of the fields.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Variations on the force law describe the magnetic force on a current-carrying wire (sometimes called **Laplace force**), and the electromotive force in a wire loop moving through a magnetic field, as described by Faraday's law of induction.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Together with Maxwell's equations, which describe how electric and magnetic fields are generated by charges and currents, the Lorentz force law forms the foundation of classical electrodynamics.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] While the law remains valid in special relativity, it breaks down at small scales where quantum effects become important.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] In particular, the intrinsic spin of particles gives rise to additional interactions with electromagnetic fields that are not accounted for by the Lorentz force.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Historians suggest that the law is implicit in a paper by James Clerk Maxwell, published in 1865.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Hendrik Lorentz arrived at a complete derivation in 1895, identifying the contribution of the electric force a few years after Oliver Heaviside correctly identified the contribution of the magnetic force.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] In general, the electric and magnetic fields depend on both position and time.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] As a charged particle moves through space, the force acting on it at any given moment depends on its current location, velocity, and the instantaneous values of the fields at that location.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The total electromagnetic force consists of two parts: the electric force *q***E**, which acts in the direction of the electric field and accelerates the particle linearly, and the magnetic force *q*(**v** × **B**), which acts perpendicularly to both the velocity and the magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Some sources refer to the Lorentz force as the sum of both components, while others use the term to refer to the magnetic part alone.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The direction of the magnetic force is often determined using the right-hand rule: if the index finger points in the direction of the velocity, and the middle finger points in the direction of the magnetic field, then the thumb points in the direction of the force (for a positive charge).
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] In a uniform magnetic field, this results in circular or helical trajectories, known as cyclotron motion.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] In many practical situations, such as the motion of electrons or ions in a plasma, the effect of a magnetic field can be approximated as a superposition of two components: a relatively fast circular motion around a point called the guiding center, and a relatively slow drift of this point.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The drift speeds may differ for various species depending on their charge states, masses, or temperatures.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] These differences may lead to electric currents or chemical separation.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] While the magnetic force affects the direction of a particle's motion, it does no mechanical work on the particle.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Thus, only the electric field can transfer energy to or from a particle and change its kinetic energy.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Some textbooks use the Lorentz force law as the fundamental definition of the electric and magnetic fields.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] That is, the fields **E** and **B** are uniquely defined at each point in space and time by the hypothetical force **F** a test particle of charge *q* and velocity **v** would experience there, even if no charge is present.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] This definition remains valid even for particles approaching the speed of light (that is, magnitude of **v**, |**v**| ≈ *c*).
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] However, some argue that using the Lorentz force law as the definition of the electric and magnetic fields is not necessarily the most fundamental approach possible.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The Lorentz force law can also be given in terms of continuous charge distributions, such as those found in conductors or plasmas.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Using Maxwell's equations and vector calculus identities, the force density can be reformulated to eliminate explicit reference to the charge and current densities.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] This form of the force law relates the energy flux in the fields to the force exerted on a charge distribution.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Inside a material, the total charge and current densities can be separated into free and bound parts.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The above-mentioned formulae use the conventions for the definition of the electric and magnetic field used with the SI, which is the most common.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] However, other conventions with the same physics (i.e. forces on e.g. an electron) are possible and used.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] In practice, the subscripts "G" and "SI" are omitted, and the used convention (and unit) must be determined from context.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] When a wire carrying a steady electric current is placed in an external magnetic field, each of the moving charges in the wire experience the Lorentz force.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Together, these forces produce a net macroscopic force on the wire.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The derivation of this equation is straight forward.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Consider a conductor of length *ℓ*, cross section *A*, and charge *q* due to electric current *I*.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] $F=NF_{q}=qvBn\ell A\sin \theta =BI\ell \sin \theta ,$ where the current, *I* = *nqvA*.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] This is the same as the equation above using the definition of the cross product.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] If the wire is not straight or the magnetic field is non-uniform, the total force can be computed by applying the formula to each infinitesimal segment of wire $\mathrm {d} {\boldsymbol {\ell }}$ , then adding up all these forces by integration.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] One application of this is Ampère's force law, which describes the attraction or repulsion between two current-carrying wires.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Each wire generates a magnetic field, described by the Biot–Savart law, which exerts a Lorentz force on the other wire.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] If the currents flow in the same direction, the wires attract; if the currents flow in opposite directions, they repel.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] This interaction provided the basis of the former definition of the ampere, as the constant current that produces a force of 2 × 10−7 newtons per metre between two straight, parallel wires one metre apart.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Another application is an induction motor.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The stator winding AC current generates a moving magnetic field which induces a current in the rotor.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The subsequent Lorentz force $\mathbf {F}$ acting on the rotor creates a torque, making the motor spin.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Hence, though the Lorentz force law does not apply when the magnetic field $\mathbf {B}$ is generated by the current I , it does apply when the current I is induced by the movement of magnetic field $\mathbf {B}$ .
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Motional EMF, induced by moving a conductor through a magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Transformer EMF, induced by a changing magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The Lorentz force acting on electric charges in a conducting loop can produce a current by pushing charges around the circuit.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] This effect is the fundamental mechanism underlying induction motors and generators.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] It is described in terms of electromotive force (emf), a quantity which plays a central role in the theory of electromagnetic induction.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] In a simple circuit with resistance R , an emf ${\mathcal {E}}$ gives rise to a current I according to the Ohm's law ${\mathcal {E}}=IR$ .
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Both components of the Lorentz force—the electric and the magnetic—can contribute to the emf in a circuit, but through different mechanisms.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The flux can change either because the loop moves or deforms over time, or because the field itself varies in time.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The sign of the induced emf is given by Lenz's law, which states that the induced current produces a magnetic field opposing the change in the original flux.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The flux rule can be derived from the Maxwell–Faraday equation and the Lorentz force law.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] In some cases, especially in extended systems, the flux rule may be difficult to apply directly or may not provide a complete description, and the full Lorentz force law must be used.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The basic mechanism behind motional emf is illustrated by a conducting rod moving through a magnetic field that is perpendicular to both the rod and its direction of motion.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Due to movement in magnetic field, the mobile electrons of the conductor experience the magnetic component (*q***v** × **B**) of the Lorentz force that drives them along the length of the rod.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] This leads to a separation of charge between the two ends of the rod.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] In the steady state, the electric field from the accumulated charge balances the magnetic force.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] If the rod is part of a closed conducting loop moving through a nonuniform magnetic field, the same effect can drive a current around the circuit.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] For instance, suppose the magnetic field is confined to a limited region of space, and the loop initially lies outside this region.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] As it moves into the field, the area of the loop that encloses magnetic flux increases, and an emf is induced.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] From the Lorentz force perspective, this is because the field exerts a magnetic force on charge carriers in the parts of the loop entering the region.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Once the entire loop lies in a uniform magnetic field and continues at constant speed, the total enclosed flux remains constant, and the emf vanishes.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] In this situation, magnetic forces on opposite sides of the loop cancel out.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] A complementary case is transformer emf, which occurs when the conducting loop remains stationary but the magnetic flux through it changes due to a time-varying magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] This can happen in two ways: either the source of the magnetic field moves, altering the field distribution through the fixed loop, or the strength of the magnetic field changes over time at a fixed location, as in the case of a powered electromagnet..
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] In either situation, no magnetic force acts on the charges, and the emf is entirely due to the electric component (*q***E**) of the Lorentz force.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] According to the Maxwell–Faraday equation, a time-varying magnetic field produces a circulating electric field, which drives current in the loop.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] This phenomenon underlies the operation of electrical machines such as synchronous generators.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The electric field induced in this way is non-conservative, meaning its line integral around a closed loop is not zero.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] From the viewpoint of special relativity, the distinction between motional and transformer emf is frame-dependent.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] In the laboratory frame, a moving loop in a static field generates emf via magnetic forces.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] But in a frame moving with the loop, the magnetic field appears time-dependent, and the emf arises from an induced electric field.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Einstein's special theory of relativity was partially motivated by the desire to better understand this link between the two effects.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] In modern terms, electric and magnetic fields are different components of a single electromagnetic field tensor, and a transformation between inertial frames mixes the two.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Early attempts to quantitatively describe the electromagnetic force were made in the mid-18th century.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] It was proposed that the force on magnetic poles, by Johann Tobias Mayer and others in 1760, and electrically charged objects, by Henry Cavendish in 1762, obeyed an inverse-square law.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] However, in both cases the experimental proof was neither complete nor conclusive.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] It was not until 1784 when Charles-Augustin de Coulomb, using a torsion balance, was able to definitively show through experiment that this was true.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Soon after the discovery in 1820 by Hans Christian Ørsted that a magnetic needle is acted on by a voltaic current, André-Marie Ampère that same year was able to devise through experimentation the formula for the angular dependence of the force between two current elements.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] In all these descriptions, the force was always described in terms of the properties of the matter involved and the distances between two masses or charges rather than in terms of electric and magnetic fields.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The modern concept of electric and magnetic fields first arose in the theories of Michael Faraday, particularly his idea of lines of force, later to be given full mathematical description by Lord Kelvin and James Clerk Maxwell.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] From a modern perspective it is possible to identify in Maxwell's 1865 formulation of his field equations a form of the Lorentz force equation in relation to electric currents, although in the time of Maxwell it was not evident how his equations related to the forces on moving charged objects.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Thomson was the first to attempt to derive from Maxwell's field equations the electromagnetic forces on a moving charged object in terms of the object's properties and external fields.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Interested in determining the electromagnetic behavior of the charged particles in cathode rays, Thomson published a paper in 1881 wherein he gave the force on the particles due to an external magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Finally, in 1895, Hendrik Lorentz derived the modern form of the formula for the electromagnetic force which includes the contributions to the total force from both the electric and the magnetic fields.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Lorentz began by abandoning the Maxwellian descriptions of the ether and conduction.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Instead, Lorentz made a distinction between matter and the luminiferous aether and sought to apply the Maxwell equations at a microscopic scale.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Using Heaviside's version of the Maxwell equations for a stationary ether and applying Lagrangian mechanics (see below), Lorentz arrived at the correct and complete form of the force law that now bears his name.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The Lagrangian for a charged particle of mass *m* and charge *q* in an electromagnetic field equivalently describes the dynamics of the particle in terms of its *energy*, rather than the force exerted on it.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The classical expression is given by: $L={\frac {m}{2}}\mathbf {\dot {r}} \cdot \mathbf {\dot {r}} +q\mathbf {A} \cdot \mathbf {\dot {r}} -q\phi$ where **A** and *ϕ* are the potential fields as above.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The quantity $V=q(\phi -\mathbf {A} \cdot \mathbf {\dot {r}} )$ can be identified as a generalized, velocity-dependent potential energy and, accordingly, $\mathbf {F}$ as a non-conservative force.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Using the Lagrangian, the equation for the Lorentz force given above can be obtained again.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The Hamiltonian can be derived from the Lagrangian using a Legendre transformation.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] For an **A** field, a particle moving with velocity **v** = **ṙ** has potential momentum $q\mathbf {A} (\mathbf {r} ,t)$ , so its potential energy is $q\mathbf {A} (\mathbf {r} ,t)\cdot \mathbf {\dot {r}}$ .
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] For a *ϕ* field, the particle's potential energy is $q\phi (\mathbf {r} ,t)$ .
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The action is the relativistic arclength of the path of the particle in spacetime, minus the potential energy contribution, plus an extra contribution which, with quantum mechanics, can be realised as a phase obtained by a charged particle moving along a vector potential.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The fields are transformed to a frame moving with constant relative velocity by: $F'^{\mu \nu }={\Lambda ^{\mu }}_{\alpha }{\Lambda ^{\nu }}_{\beta }F^{\alpha \beta }\,,$ where Λ*μ**α* is the Lorentz transformation tensor.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The dot product with the vector $\gamma _{0}$ pulls a vector (in the space algebra) from the translational part, while the wedge-product creates a trivector (in the space algebra) who is dual to a vector which is the usual magnetic field vector.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Note that the order is important because between a bivector and a vector the dot product is anti-symmetric.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Upon a spacetime split like one can obtain the velocity, and fields as above yielding the usual expression.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] where D is the covariant differential in general relativity.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] In quantum mechanics, particles are described by wavefunctions whose evolution is governed by the Schrödinger equation.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] While this formulation does not involve forces explicitly, it extends the framework of Hamiltonian mechanics, by incorporating interactions with electromagnetic fields through potential terms in the Hamiltonian.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] The key difference is that in quantum mechanics, position $\mathbf {r}$ and momentum ${\hat {\mathbf {p} }}$ are operators that do not commute.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] As a result, quantum dynamics incorporate fundamentally different behavior such as wave interference and quantization.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Unlike in classical physics, where only electric and magnetic fields influence particle motion, quantum mechanics allows the electromagnetic potentials themselves to produce observable effects.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] This is exemplified by the Aharonov–Bohm effect, in which a charged particle passes through a region with zero electric and magnetic fields but encircles a magnetic flux confined to an inaccessible area.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Although the classical Lorentz force is zero along the particle's path, the interference pattern observed on a screen shifts depending on the enclosed magnetic flux, revealing the physical significance of the vector potential in quantum mechanics.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Nevertheless, the classical Lorentz force law emerges as an approximation to the quantum dynamics: according to the Ehrenfest theorem, the expectation value of the momentum operator evolves according to an equation that resembles the classical Lorentz force law.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Even in the Aharonov–Bohm setup, the average motion of a wave packet follows the classical trajectory.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Quantum particles such as electrons also possess intrinsic spin, which introduces additional electromagnetic interactions beyond those described by the classical Lorentz force.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] This term leads to spin-dependent forces absent in the classical theory.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] A complete relativistic treatment is given by the Dirac equation, which incorporates spin and electromagnetic interactions through minimal coupling, and correctly predicts features such as the electron's gyromagnetic ratio.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] In many real-world applications, the Lorentz force is insufficient to accurately describe the collective behavior of charged particles, both in practice and on a fundamental level.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] Real systems involve many interacting particles that also generate their own fields **E** and **B**.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] To account for these collective effects—such as currents, flows, and plasmas—more complex equations are required, such as the Boltzmann equation, the Fokker–Planck equation or the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:electromagnetism/lorentz-force] These models go beyond single-particle dynamics, incorporating particle interactions and self-consistent field generation, and are central to fields like magnetohydrodynamics, electrohydrodynamics, and plasma physics, as well as to the understanding of astrophysical and superconducting phenomena.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] In magnetism and electromagnetism, **magnetic field** is a physical property of space that quantifies the magnetic influence at a given location.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Magnetic fields deflect moving electric charges (including electric currents), apply torques on magnets to twist them in the direction of the magnetic field, and attract or repel magnets and magnetic material such as iron.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] In addition, a time-varying magnetic field induces electrical currents.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Magnetic fields are created by magnetic materials and by moving electric charges (including electrical current).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The latter is important in creating electromagnets: devices that precisely control magnetic fields by changing the current through the electromagnet.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Magnetic fields are used throughout modern science and technology.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] In electrical engineering and electromechanics it is important in the design and use of electric motors, generators, transformers, electromagnets, and inductors among many other devices.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] In material science, magnetic forces give information about the charge carriers in a material through the Hall effect in addition to other uses.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] In geology and geophysics, Earth's magnetic field gives information about earth's interior while local magnetic field measurements are used in mineral exploration and other measurements.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Too, Earth's magnetic field creates a magnetosphere which shields the Earth's ozone layer and the rest of the planet from the solar wind.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] In physics the relationship between the magnetic and electric fields forms the field of electrodynamics which is important to understand a wide range of phenomena including light (also known as electromagnetic radiation) and the properties of antenna and transmission lines.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Since both strength and direction of a magnetic field may vary with location, it is described mathematically by assigning a vector to each point of space, making it a vector field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] There are two different, but closely related, vector fields which are called "magnetic field".
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] While the best names for these fields is the subject of long running debate, the underlying physics is uncontested.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The international ISO 80000-6 standard defines **magnetic field** as "that component of an electromagnetic field which is characterized by the magnetic field strength vector **H** and the magnetic flux density vector **B**." This standard also defines **B** and **H** as given in the sections below.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] While there is wide agreement on these definitions of **B** and **H**, there are many alternative names for both (see sidebars in the corresponding sections).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Also known as **magnetic flux density**, the magnetic **B** field causes magnetic forces, magnetic torques and electromagnetic induction.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Therefore, it can be defined by any equation that describes these phenomena.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Here **F** is the force on the particle, *q* is the particle's electric charge, **E** is the external electric field, **v**, is the particle's velocity, and × denotes the cross product.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] For more details see Lorentz Force or the § Magnetic force on a charged particle section below.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The SI unit of **B** is tesla (symbol: T).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The Gaussian-cgs unit of **B** is the gauss (symbol: G).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] (The conversion is 1 T ≘ 10000 G.) One nanotesla corresponds to 1 gamma (symbol: γ).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] While **B** creates magnetic forces and torques on objects and induces currents in conducting wires, it is not always easy to calculate.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] where $\mu _{0}$ is the vacuum permeability, and **M** is the magnetization vector which represents how magnetized a given region of material is and is defined below.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] In a vacuum, **B** = μ0**H** making them equivalent to each other.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Defined this way, **H** can in many circumstance be treated as if it is only due to electrical currents with corrections accounting for **H** due to nearby magnetic material.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] In any case, **B** still needs to be calculated from **H** if forces, torques, induced currents, or energy changes need to be calculated.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The SI unit of **H** is the ampere per metre (A/m) and the Gaussian unit is the oersted (Oe).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Instruments used to measure the local magnetic **B**-field are known as a magnetometers.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Important classes of magnetometers include induction magnetometers (or search-coil magnetometers) which measure only varying magnetic fields, rotating coil magnetometers, Hall effect magnetometers, NMR magnetometers, SQUID magnetometers, and fluxgate magnetometers.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The magnetic fields of distant astronomical objects are measured through their effects on local charged particles.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] For instance, electrons spiraling around a field line produce synchrotron radiation that is detectable in radio waves.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The finest precision for a magnetic field measurement was attained by Gravity Probe B at 5 aT (5×10−18 T).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The **H**-field cannot be directly measured but can be inferred from the currents that create it.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] sprinkled on paper placed above a bar magnet.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] needles point in the direction of the local magnetic field, towards a magnet's south pole and away from its north pole.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Magnetic field can be visualized by a set of *magnetic field lines*, that follow the direction of the field at each point.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The direction of the magnetic field at any point is parallel to the direction of nearby field lines, and the local density of field lines can be made proportional to its strength.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Magnetic field lines are like streamlines in fluid flow, in that they represent a continuous distribution, and a different resolution would show more or fewer lines.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] An advantage of using magnetic field lines as a representation is that many laws of magnetism (and electromagnetism) can be stated completely and concisely using simple concepts such as the "number" of field lines through a surface.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] These concepts can then be "translated" to their mathematical form.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] For example, the number of field lines through a given surface is the surface integral of the magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] This article uses almost entirely the SI unit system.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] But other unit systems, most importantly the Gaussian unit system (which is the most used system of cgs units for electromagnetism), are still being used in some disciplines, countries, and textbooks.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The equations for each unit system can be, and often are, different for different unit systems.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Moving electric charges including electrical currents experience a force due to magnetic **B** fields.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] A charged particle moving in a **B**-field experiences a *sideways* force that is proportional to the strength of the magnetic field, the component of the velocity that is perpendicular to the magnetic field and the charge of the particle.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] where **F** is the force, *q* is the electric charge of the particle, **v** is the instantaneous velocity of the particle, and **B** is the magnetic field (in teslas).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The direction of force on the charge can be determined by the right-hand rule (see the figure).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The Lorentz force is always perpendicular to both the velocity of the particle and the magnetic field that created it.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] When a charged particle moves in a static magnetic field, it traces a helical path in which the helix axis is parallel to the magnetic field, and in which the speed of the particle remains constant.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] This force (on a macroscopic current) is often referred to as the *Laplace force*.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] where I is the current and **ℓ** is a vector whose magnitude is the length of the wire, and whose direction is along the wire, aligned with the direction of the current.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] This force creates an attractive/repulsive force between 2 parallel wires as the current through each produces a magnetic field that pushes/pulls on the other.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Too, a loop of current in a magnetic field will experience a torque due to the different direction of the force on different sides of the loop as describe in the next section.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] A magnetic field acting on a current carrying loop produces both a torque and a net force (if the magnetic field is non-uniform).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] This effect is important for driving certain types of motors and in modeling forces and torques on atoms.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Calculating the torque on a rectangular loop is straightforward.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The diagram to the right shows a rectangular loop of current in a uniform magnetic **B** field (with a direction indicated by the green arrows).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] For simplicity the loop is aligned so that it is along the direction of the magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The magnetic force on opposite sides of the loop are equal and opposite producing no net force on the loop.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The forces on the short sides (here shown as violet arrows), though, produce a net torque equal to the product of the force and the perpendicular distance between them.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Denoting the short side length as b, the magnitude of that force is F = IBb using the equation for the magnetic force on a straight wire given in the previous section.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The magnitude of the net torque (along dashed axis) is therefore N = IabB.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Here the direction of the area **A** is the normal to the area as determined by the right hand grip rule of the current loop.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] While derived for a rectangular loop this equation is valid for a flat loop of any shape and orientation.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] As described above, there is no net force on a loop in a uniform magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] However, non-uniform magnetic fields do produce a net force.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] This net force tends to pull the object in direction of the stronger magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] For a sufficiently small current loop, the details of the current loop such as it shape, area, orientation, and current around the loop are all hidden in **m** and otherwise do not matter.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] All magnetic dipoles with the same dipole moment **m** are affected the same way.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] This force tends to push the magnetic dipole into the direction of increasing **B**.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] All moving charged particles produce magnetic fields.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Moving point charges, such as electrons, produce complicated but well known magnetic fields that depend on the charge, velocity, and acceleration of the particles.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] These equations become much simpler when the moving charges form a steady state electrical current, the study of which is called magnetostatics.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] In general, magnetic field lines form concentric circles around a current-carrying wire.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The direction of such a magnetic field can be determined by using the "right-hand grip rule" (see figure at right).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The strength of the magnetic field decreases with distance from the wire.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] where *r* is the perpendicular distance to the wire.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The direction ${\hat {\phi }}$ of the magnetic field is tangent to a circle perpendicular to the wire according to the right hand rule.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Bending a current-carrying wire into a loop concentrates the magnetic field inside the loop while weakening it outside.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Bending a wire into multiple closely spaced loops to form a coil or 'solenoid' enhances this effect.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] A device so formed around an iron core may act as an electromagnet, generating a strong, well-controlled magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] An infinitely long solenoid has a uniform magnetic field inside, and no magnetic field outside.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] where n is the number of turns per unit length of the solenoid and the direction of **H** is along the length of the solenoid.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] A finite length solenoid produces a more complicated magnetic field that can be evaluated mathematically.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] For other examples of using the Biot-Savart law to calculate the magnetic fields for other common current configurations see #Common formulæ below.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] where $\mathbf {m} =I\mathbf {A} =I(\pi a^{2}\mathbf {\hat {z}} )$ is the same magnetic dipole moment used in calculating the force and torque on a loop of current in #Net force and torque on a magnetic dipole above.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Calculating the on-axis magnetic fields of a square loop (and other flat geometries) yields similar equations that have the same equation at long distances as the circle: $\mathbf {H} ={\frac {\mathbf {m} }{2\pi z^{3}}}$ .
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Calculating the magnetic field at a arbitrary location **r** (not just on-axis) from an arbitrarily shaped current loop involves advanced math.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] This equation shows that at sufficiently long distances the detailed geometry of a magnet can be replaced by a single quantity, the magnetic dipole moment **m**.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] This equation, therefore makes a good model for the magnetic field of atoms and can be extended to describe magnetic material.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Too, it has some utility in calculating the long distance force between magnets.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] where the line integral is over any arbitrary loop and $I_{\text{enc}}$ is the current enclosed by that loop.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The $I_{\text{enc}}$ is slightly different for the 2 equations in that **B** includes the difficult to calculate bound current in magnetic material while **H** does not.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Ampère's law is always valid for steady currents and can be used to easily calculate the magnetic fields of certain highly symmetric situations such as an infinite wire or an infinite solenoid.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] In a modified form that accounts for time varying electric fields, Ampère's law is one of four Maxwell's equations that describe electricity and magnetism.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Magnets are objects that both create their own magnetic field and respond to the magnetic field of other magnets and magnetized materials.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The interaction between magnets and their interaction with magnetic field is extremely complicated.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The correct description involves describing each magnet as being made of many small volumes of magnetic material each of which creates its own magnetic field and responds to the magnetic field of the other volumes.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Such models are often extremely complex.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Fortunately, in many cases, it is sufficient to understand magnets as objects that have 2 equal but opposite magnetic poles: the magnetic north and south poles.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Opposite poles attract with a force that increases with smaller distances while like poles repel in the same way.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Such a model is called a *magnetic pole model* and it, in some cases described below, can be used to make good quantitative predictions.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Specifying the force between magnets is quite complicated because it depends on the strength and orientation of both magnets and their distance and direction relative to each other.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The force is particularly sensitive to rotations of the magnets due to magnetic torque.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The force on each magnet depends on its magnetic moment and the magnetic field of the other.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] For short distances (small r) the forces can be quite strong but it decreases quite rapidly (1/r4) for large distances.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] For 2 sufficiently small magnets, such as 2 atoms far enough away from each other, the magnetic force can be represented as that of two infinitesimally small dipoles.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] where **r** is the distance-vector from dipole moment **m**1 to dipole moment **m**2, with *r* = ‖***r***‖.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The force acting on **m**1 is in the opposite direction.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The net force depends on the orientation of both dipole moments relative to each other and relative to the distance-vector between them and it decreases rapidly (proportional to 1/r4).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] For moderate distances it is often to sufficient model the force between magnets as the ***H**-field* of one magnet pushes and pulls on *both* poles of a second magnet.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] If this **H**-field is the same at both poles of the second magnet then there is no net force on that magnet since the force is opposite for opposite poles.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] If, however, the magnetic field of the first magnet is *nonuniform* (such as the **H** near one of its poles), each pole of the second magnet sees a different field and is subject to a different force.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] This difference in the two forces moves the magnet in the direction of increasing magnetic field and may also cause a net torque.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] If both poles are small enough to be represented as single points then they can be considered to be point magnetic charges.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] where qm1 and qm2 are the **magnetic pole strengths** of each magnet (SI unit: ampere-meter), *μ* is the permeability of the intervening medium, and **r** is the separation distance between the 2 poles.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Note that for 2 magnets (each having 2 poles) the sum of 4 forces is needed: each of the 2 poles of one magnet exerts a separate force on each of the 2 poles of the second magnet.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The pole description is useful to practicing magneticians who design real-world magnets, but real magnets have a pole distribution more complex than a single north and south.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Therefore, implementation of the pole idea is not simple.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] In some cases, one of the more complex formulas given below will be more useful.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The mechanical force between two nearby magnetized surfaces can be calculated with the following equation.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] where *A* is the surface area of the magnetic pole and μ0 is the permeability of free space.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] This equation is also valid for the force of a magnetic pole on iron that is either almost touching or touching the magnetic pole.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] If two like poles of two separate magnets are brought near each other, and one of the magnets is allowed to turn, it promptly rotates to align itself with the first.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] In this example, the magnetic field of the stationary magnet creates a *magnetic torque* on the magnet that is free to rotate.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] This magnetic torque **N** tends to align a magnet's poles with the magnetic field lines.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] A compass, therefore, turns to align itself with Earth's magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] field induces the same torque on a current loop with the same magnetic dipole moment.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] where × represents the vector cross product.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] This equation includes all of the qualitative information included above.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] There is no torque on a magnet if **m** is in the same direction as the magnetic field, since the cross product is zero for two vectors that are in the same direction.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Further, all other orientations feel a torque that twists them toward the direction of magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Most materials respond to an applied magnetic field by becoming magnetized (at least temporarily) which causes them to produce their own magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Typically, the response is weak and exists only when the magnetic field is applied.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] There are many different types of material that respond differently to the applied magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The term *magnet* is typically reserved for objects that produce their own persistent magnetic field even in the absence of an applied magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Only certain classes of materials can do this.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Most materials, however, produce a magnetic field in response to an applied magnetic field – a phenomenon known as magnetism.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] There are several types of magnetism, and all materials exhibit at least one of them.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The overall magnetic behavior of a material can vary widely, depending on the structure of the material, particularly on its electron configuration.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] It can also vary with temperature, pressure, and magnetic field strength such that a given material may have more than one magnetic phase.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] In the case of paramagnetism and diamagnetism, the relationship between the applied magnetic field and the magnetization is often linear.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] However, superconductors and ferromagnets have a more complicated relation between the applied magnetic field and magnetization produced (see magnetic hysteresis).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] *Permanent magnets* are objects that produce their own persistent magnetic fields.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] They are made of ferromagnetic materials, such as iron and nickel, that have been magnetized.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The magnetic field of magnetized material is created at the atomic level.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The proper description of this effect involves quantum mechanics.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Fortunately, the net effect of adding up these magnetic interactions can often be calculated using much simpler models for the magnetic field created by the constituent atoms in the magnetic material.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] This occurs because at large enough distance (or equivalently for small enough magnets) all the magnetic properties of any magnetic object can be described by a single (vector) quantity, the magnetic dipole moment, **m**.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] (See § Magnetic field of a flat loop of current (magnetic dipole) and § Net force and torque on a magnetic dipole above).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Objects that can be modeled this way, for example atoms, are called magnetic dipoles.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Magnetic dipoles, therefore, are the building blocks of magnetization.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The magnetic field produced by magnetized material then is the net magnetic field of these dipoles.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Too, the net force (and torque) on a magnetized material is a result of adding up the forces and torques on the individual dipoles that make up the magnetized material.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The *magnetization* vector field **M** represents how strongly a region of material is magnetized.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] It is defined as the net magnetic dipole moment per unit volume of that region.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The magnetization of a uniformly magnetized magnet is therefore a constant, equal to the magnetic moment **m** of the magnet divided by its volume.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Since the SI unit of magnetic moment is A⋅m2, the SI unit of magnetization **M** is ampere per meter, identical to that of the **H**-field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The magnetization **M** field of a region points in the direction of the average magnetic dipole moment in that region.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Magnetization field lines, therefore, begin (inside the magnetized material) near the magnetic south pole and ends (inside the magnetized material) near the magnetic north pole.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] In the Amperian loop model, the magnetization is due to combining many tiny magnetic dipole loops to form a resultant current called *bound current*.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] This bound current, then, is the source of the magnetic **B** field due to the magnet.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] where the integral is a line integral over any closed loop and *I*b is the bound current enclosed by that closed loop.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Unlike the magnetic **B** field-lines which cannot begin nor end, magnetization field lines can begin and end.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Indeed they must begin and end where they intersects the boundary of the magnetized material (at magnetic poles) because the magnetization field only exists inside of a material.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] This is analogous to electric field-lines which begin and end at electrical charges.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] where the integral is a closed surface integral over the closed surface *S* and *q*M is the "magnetic charge" (in units of magnetic flux) enclosed by *S*.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] (A closed surface completely surrounds a region with no holes to let any field lines escape.) The negative sign occurs because the magnetization field moves from south to north.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] No such magnetic charge exists; rather it is a convenient analogy that allows the use of much of the machinery developed for electrostatics with electric charge to be applied to magnetization with its fictitious magnetic charge.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] For example the net magnetic charge of a pole is defined as a **magnetic pole strength** qm.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] From this equation, it is evident that outside of a magnetic material (where $\mathbf {M} =0$ ) that $\mathbf {B} =\mu _{0}\mathbf {H}$ .
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Outside a magnetic material, therefore, **B** and **H** are functionally identical just with different units since $\mu _{0}$ is a constant.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] where If represents the 'free current' enclosed by the loop so that the line integral of **H** does not depend at all on the bound currents.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] which does not depend on the free currents.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The magnetic **H**-field, therefore, re-factors the bound current in terms of "magnetic charges".
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The **H** field lines loop only around "free current" and, unlike the magnetic **B** field, begins and ends near magnetic poles as well.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] where *μ* is a material dependent parameter called the permeability.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] In some cases the permeability may be a second rank tensor so that **H** may not point in the same direction as **B**.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] These relations between **B** and **H** are examples of constitutive equations.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] In many real world applications such as small magnetic object inside of an extended applied magnetic field, the constitutive relation is not sufficient even if the material is linear.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] This is because the **H**-field that the material experiences is not the same as the **H** applied.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] In such cases, the magnetic field can still be calculated but care must be taken to distinguish the change of the magnetic field across the boundary of the magnetic object.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] where the subscript t represents the tangential component of **H** and n represents its normal component.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] For time varying magnetic fields (and more generally changing electrical currents or accelerating electrical charges), the magnetic and electric fields become linked such that a change in one induces the other.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Together, the electric and magnetic fields form an electromagnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The study of how the electric and magnetic fields interact in this way is called electrodynamics and includes many phenomenon that are important in physics and electrical engineering.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] It underlies transformers, and the generation and transmission of electrical power through wires and through space in the form of electromagnetic radiation of which light is one form.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Too, it allow magnetic fields to store and transmit energy.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] A time varying magnetic field through a loop of wire induces a current (more properly an EMF) through that loop.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] This is known as electromagnetic induction and is important for many electronic devices such as inductors, transformers, and electrical generators.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] where ${\mathcal {E}}$ is the electromotive force (or *EMF*, the voltage generated around a closed loop) and Φ is the magnetic flux—the product of the area times the magnetic field normal to that area.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] (This definition of magnetic flux is why **B** is often referred to as *magnetic flux density*.) The negative sign represents the fact that any current generated by a changing magnetic field in a coil produces a magnetic field that *opposes* the *change* in the magnetic field that induced it.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Energy is needed to generate a magnetic field both to work against the electric field that a changing magnetic field creates and to change the magnetization of any material within the magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] For non-dispersive materials, the energy used to magnetize the material is released when the magnetic field is destroyed so that the energy can be modeled as being stored in the magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The above equation cannot be used for nonlinear materials, though.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Once the relationship between **H** and **B** is known this equation is used to determine the work needed to reach a given magnetic state.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] For hysteretic materials such as ferromagnets and superconductors, the work needed also depends on how the magnetic field is created.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] For linear non-dispersive materials, though, the general equation leads directly to the simpler energy density equation given above.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Magnetic field, together with the electric field, transmit electrical power.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Note that this power includes both the power transmitted by the electric and magnetic fields and the energy absorbed and emitted by magnetizing and polarizing the material.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Too, this equation only works for linear non-dispersive materials.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] This equations is also valid in a vacuum where **H** = **B**/μ0.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The time average of the poynting vector is known as irradiance and is an important quantity in optics that describes how intense light is at a given point.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] It is sometimes useful to calculate the magnetic field for a given set of time varying charges and currents, without having to use the complicated equations used to directly calculate it.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] An example of this is calculating the magnetic field of a light wave as it reflects and refracts at a surface.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] In such cases Maxwell's equations are used to solve for both the magnetic and electric fields.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Maxwell's equations are a powerful set of differential equations that allows the calculation of the magnetic and electric fields for simple (and complex using computers and Finite Element Analysis) geometries.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Maxwell's Equations together with the Lorentz force law form a complete description of classical electrodynamics including both electricity and magnetism.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Maxwell's equations takes advantage of the fact that all vector fields (such as the electric and magnetic fields) can be expressed in terms of 2 types of *sources* and an appropriate set of boundary conditions.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The first type of *source* (an outflow source) causes the vector field to flow out (or in for a sink) to a given point.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The second (or circulation) source causes the vector field to rotate around a given point (forming vortices).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Both of these sources have well defined definitions and can be calculated from the vector field they create using a well-understood vector operator.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The divergence of a vector field **A**, **∇** · **A** is defined such that applying the divergence operator to a given vector field will yield the outflow sources.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The curl is defined such that **∇** × **A** yields the circulation source.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] An example of the power of these vector operators is: since it is an experimental fact that magnetic charges do not exist (and therefore there are no source nor sinks of **B**) the divergence of **B** must be zero, **∇** · **B** = 0, which is one of Maxwell's equations.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Maxwell's equation has 2 major versions: a microscopic version which necessitates knowing all of the charges and currents (including the complex ones at the atomic level) and the macroscopic version which depends only on the know 'free' charge and 'free' currents.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] Here the term 'free' means any charge or current that is directly controlled by the experiment and does not include the atomic level 'bound' charges and currents in a material which happen as a response to the electric and magnetic fields present in that material.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] In these equations, $\mathbf {D}$ is the electric displacement field, $\mathbf {E}$ the electric field, $\rho _{f}$ the free electric charge density, and $\mathbf {J} _{f}$ the free current density.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The first of Maxwell's equations is known as Gauss' Law but does not involve magnetic field so does not warrant further discussion here.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The second equation is Gauss' law for magnetism which reflects the non-existence of magnetic charge and allows **B** to be determined as the curl of a vector potential **A**.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] The third equation is Faraday's law of induction.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p01] And, the fourth equation is Ampère's law with Maxwell's correction.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] In deriving advanced equations and in advanced topics such as quantum mechanics and relativity, it is often easier to work with a *potential formulation* of electrodynamics rather than in terms of the electric and magnetic fields.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The vector potential, ***A*** given by this form may be interpreted as a *generalized potential momentum per unit charge* just as *φ* is interpreted as a *generalized potential energy per unit charge*.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] There are multiple choices one can make for the potential fields that satisfy the above condition.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] However, the choice of potentials is represented by its respective gauge condition.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Maxwell's equations when expressed in terms of the potentials can be cast into a form that explicitly agrees with special relativity.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Together, **A** and *φ* form the four-potential.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Using the four potential instead of electric and magnetic fields is much simpler—and it can be easily adapted to work with quantum mechanics.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Magnetic field is inherently a relativistic phenomena.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] More specifically, both electric and magnetic fields are the same phenomenon as seen in different reference frames: An electric force perceived by one observer may be perceived by another (in a different frame of reference) as a magnetic force, or a mixture of electric and magnetic forces.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] (Here different reference frames means one reference frame is moving relative to the other.) For relativistic phenomena, a lorentz transformation must be used to move (or transform) from one reference system to another.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] It is a straightforward task to show how the electric and magnetic fields transform from one reference frame to another.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The transformation rules, however are quite messy.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] One simple example is to examine how Coulomb's Law (which is a pure electric field of a charged particle in it own rest frame) transforms to a moving reference frame.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Formally, special relativity combines the electric and magnetic fields into a rank-2 tensor, called the *electromagnetic tensor*.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Changing reference frames *mixes* these components.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] This is analogous to the way that special relativity *mixes* space and time into spacetime, and mass, momentum, and energy into four-momentum.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Similarly, the energy stored in a magnetic field is mixed with the energy stored in an electric field in the electromagnetic stress–energy tensor.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The solution of maxwell's equations for electric and magnetic field of a point charge is expressed in terms of retarded time or the time at which the particle in the past causes the field at the point, given that the influence travels across space at the speed of light.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] where q is the charge of the point source, $n_{s}$ is a unit vector pointing from charged particle to the point in space, ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}_{s}(t)$ is the velocity of the particle divided by the speed of light and $\gamma (t)$ is the corresponding Lorentz factor.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The classical electromagnetic field incorporated into quantum mechanics forms what is known as the semi-classical theory of radiation.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] However, it is not able to make experimentally observed predictions such as spontaneous emission process or Lamb shift implying the need for quantization of fields.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] In modern physics, the electromagnetic field is understood to be not a *classical* field, but rather a quantum field; it is represented not as a vector of three numbers at each point, but as a vector of three quantum operators at each point.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The most accurate modern description of the electromagnetic interaction (and much else) is *quantum electrodynamics* (QED), which is incorporated into a more complete theory known as the *Standard Model of particle physics*.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] In QED, the magnitude of the electromagnetic interactions between charged particles (and their antiparticles) is computed using perturbation theory.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] These rather complex formulas produce a remarkable pictorial representation as Feynman diagrams in which virtual photons are exchanged.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Predictions of QED agree with experiments to an extremely high degree of accuracy: currently about 10−12 (and limited by experimental errors); for details see precision tests of QED.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] This makes QED one of the most accurate physical theories constructed thus far.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] All equations in this article are in the classical approximation, which is less accurate than the quantum description mentioned here.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] However, under most everyday circumstances, the difference between the two theories is negligible.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The Earth's magnetic field is produced by convection of a liquid iron alloy in the outer core.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] In a dynamo process, the movements drive a feedback process in which electric currents create electric and magnetic fields that in turn act on the currents.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The field at the surface of the Earth is approximately the same as if a giant bar magnet were positioned at the center of the Earth and tilted at an angle of about 11° off the rotational axis of the Earth (see the figure).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The north pole of a magnetic compass needle points roughly north, toward the North Magnetic Pole.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] However, because a magnetic pole is attracted to its opposite, the North Magnetic Pole is actually the south pole of the geomagnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] This confusion in terminology arises because the pole of a magnet is defined by the geographical direction it points.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Earth's magnetic field is not constant—the strength of the field and the location of its poles vary.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Moreover, the poles periodically reverse their orientation in a process called geomagnetic reversal.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The most recent reversal occurred 780,000 years ago.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Measuring the Earths' magnetic field is a very useful tool in mineral exploration, oil exploration, and geological mapping.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] To cover large areas with uniform data, aircraft such as helicopters, airplanes, and drones are employed.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The amount of detail is a function of flight height and sample density, in addition to instrument sensitivity.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] For surveys, drones are used which helps greatly in the process.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Aeromagnetic surveys are also used to perform reconnaissance mapping of unexploded ordnance.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The *rotating magnetic field* is a common design principle in the operation of alternating-current motors.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] A permanent magnet in such a field rotates so as to maintain its alignment with the external field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Magnetic torque is used to drive electric motors.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] In one simple motor design, a magnet is fixed to a freely rotating shaft and is subjected to a magnetic field from an array of electromagnets.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] By continuously switching the electric current through each of the electromagnets, thereby flipping the polarity of their magnetic fields, like poles are kept next to the rotor; the resultant torque is transferred to the shaft.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] A rotating magnetic field can be constructed using two coils at right angles with a phase difference of 90 degrees between their AC currents.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] In practice, three-phase systems are used where the three currents are equal in magnitude and have a phase difference of 120 degrees.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Three similar coils at mutual geometrical angles of 120 degrees create the rotating magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The ability of the three-phase system to create a rotating field, utilized in electric motors, is one of the main reasons why three-phase systems dominate the world's electrical power supply systems.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Synchronous motors use DC-voltage-fed rotor windings, which lets the excitation of the machine be controlled—and induction motors use short-circuited rotors (instead of a magnet) following the rotating magnetic field of a multicoiled stator.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The short-circuited turns of the rotor develop eddy currents induced by the rotating field of the stator, and these currents in turn produce a torque on the rotor through the Lorentz force.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The Italian physicist Galileo Ferraris and the Serbian-American electrical engineer Nikola Tesla independently researched the use of rotating magnetic fields in electric motors.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] In 1888, Ferraris published his research in a paper to the *Royal Academy of Sciences* in Turin and Tesla gained U.S. patent 381,968 for his work.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] An important use of **H** is in *magnetic circuits*.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] A magnetic circuit is made up of one or more closed loop paths containing a magnetic flux.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The flux is usually generated by permanent magnets or electromagnets and confined to the path by magnetic cores consisting of ferromagnetic materials like iron, although there may be air gaps or other materials in the path.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Magnetic circuits are employed to efficiently channel magnetic fields in many devices such as electric motors, generators, transformers, relays, lifting electromagnets, SQUIDs, galvanometers, and magnetic recording heads.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The relation between the magnetic properties of a magnetic circuit can be described by Hopkinson's law, which bears a superficial resemblance to Ohm's law in electrical circuits, resulting in a one-to-one correspondence between properties of a magnetic circuit and an analogous electric circuit.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Using this concept the magnetic fields of complex devices such as transformers can be quickly solved using the methods and techniques developed for electrical circuits.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] where ${\textstyle \Phi =\int \mathbf {B} \cdot \mathrm {d} \mathbf {A} }$ is the magnetic flux in the circuit, ${\textstyle F=\int \mathbf {H} \cdot \mathrm {d} {\boldsymbol {\ell }}}$ is the magnetomotive force applied to the circuit, and *R*m is the magnetic reluctance of the circuit.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Here the reluctance *R*m is a quantity similar in nature to resistance for the flux.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Using this analogy it is straightforward to calculate the magnetic flux of complicated magnetic field geometries, by using all the available techniques of circuit theory.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Magnetic levitation is used for maglev trains, contactless melting, magnetic bearings, and for product display purposes.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Magnetic field affects materials in a large number of ways.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The charge carriers of a current-carrying conductor placed in a transverse magnetic field experience a sideways Lorentz force; this results in a charge separation in a direction perpendicular to the current and to the magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The resultant voltage in that direction is proportional to the applied magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The *Hall effect* is often used to measure the magnitude of a magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] It is used as well to find the sign of the dominant charge carriers in materials such as semiconductors (negative electrons or positive holes).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The largest magnitude magnetic field produced over a macroscopic volume outside a lab setting is 2.8 kT (VNIIEF in Sarov, Russia, 1998).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The largest magnitude magnetic field produced in a laboratory over a macroscopic volume was 1.2 kT by researchers at the University of Tokyo in 2018.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The largest magnitude microscopic magnetic fields produced in a laboratory occur in particle accelerators, such as RHIC, inside the collisions of heavy ions, where microscopic fields reach 1014 T.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Magnetars have the strongest known macroscopic magnetic fields of any naturally occurring object, ranging from 0.1 to 100 GT (108 to 1011 T).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] While magnets and some properties of magnetism were known to ancient societies, the research of magnetic fields began in 1269 when French scholar Petrus Peregrinus de Maricourt mapped out the magnetic field on the surface of a spherical magnet using iron needles.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Noting the resulting field lines crossed at two points he named those points "poles" in analogy to Earth's poles.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] He also articulated the principle that magnets always have both a north and south pole, no matter how finely one slices them.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] In 1600 (almost three centuries later), William Gilbert of Colchester published *De Magnete*.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] In *De Magnete*, Gilbert replicated Petrus Peregrinus' work and was the first to state explicitly that Earth is a magnet.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Too, he argued that electricity and magnetism were separate phenomenon.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] In 1750, John Michell stated that magnetic poles attract and repel in accordance with an inverse square law Charles-Augustin de Coulomb experimentally verified this in 1785 and stated explicitly that north and south poles cannot be separated.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Building on this force between poles, Siméon Denis Poisson (1781–1840) created the first successful model of the magnetic field, which he presented in 1824.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Three discoveries in 1820 challenged this foundation of magnetism.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Hans Christian Ørsted demonstrated that a current-carrying wire is surrounded by a circular magnetic field.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Then André-Marie Ampère showed that parallel wires with currents attract one another if the currents are in the same direction and repel if they are in opposite directions.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Finally, Jean-Baptiste Biot and Félix Savart announced empirical results about the forces that a current-carrying long, straight wire exerted on a small magnet, determining the forces were inversely proportional to the perpendicular distance from the wire to the magnet.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Laplace later deduced a law of force based on the differential action of a differential section of the wire, which became known as the Biot–Savart law, as Laplace did not publish his findings.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Extending these experiments, Ampère published his own successful model of magnetism in 1825.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] In it, he showed the equivalence of electrical currents to magnets and proposed that magnetism is due to perpetually flowing loops of current instead of the dipoles of magnetic charge in Poisson's model.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Further, Ampère derived both Ampère's force law describing the force between two currents and Ampère's law, which, like the Biot–Savart law, correctly described the magnetic field generated by a steady current.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Also in his 1825 work, Ampère introduced the term electrodynamics to describe the relationship between electricity and magnetism.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] In 1831, Michael Faraday discovered electromagnetic induction when he found that a changing magnetic field generates an encircling electric field, formulating what is now known as Faraday's law of induction.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Later, Franz Ernst Neumann proved that, for a moving conductor in a magnetic field, induction is a consequence of Ampère's force law.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] In the process, he introduced the magnetic vector potential, which was later shown to be equivalent to the underlying mechanism proposed by Faraday.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] In 1850, Lord Kelvin, then known as William Thomson, distinguished between two magnetic fields now denoted **H** and **B**.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The former applied to Poisson's model and the latter to Ampère's model and induction.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Further, he derived how **H** and **B** relate to each other and coined the term *permeability*.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Between 1861 and 1865, James Clerk Maxwell developed and published Maxwell's equations, which explained and united all of classical electricity and magnetism.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The first set of these equations was published in a paper entitled *On Physical Lines of Force* in 1861.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] These equations were valid but incomplete.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Maxwell completed his set of equations in his later 1865 paper *A Dynamical Theory of the Electromagnetic Field* and demonstrated the fact that light is an electromagnetic wave.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Heinrich Hertz published papers in 1887 and 1888 experimentally confirming this fact.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] In 1887, Tesla developed an induction motor that ran on alternating current.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The motor used polyphase current, which generated a rotating magnetic field to turn the motor (a principle that Tesla claimed to have conceived in 1882).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Tesla received a patent for his electric motor in May 1888.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] In 1885, Galileo Ferraris independently researched rotating magnetic fields and subsequently published his research in a paper to the *Royal Academy of Sciences* in Turin, just two months before Tesla was awarded his patent, in March 1888.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] The twentieth century showed that classical electrodynamics is already consistent with special relativity, and extended classical electrodynamics to work with quantum mechanics.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Albert Einstein, in his paper of 1905 that established relativity, showed that both the electric and magnetic fields are part of the same phenomena viewed from different reference frames.
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] Finally, the emergent field of quantum mechanics was merged with electrodynamics to form quantum electrodynamics (or QED).
[src:electromagnetism/magnetic-field-p02] QED mathematically describes all phenomena involving electrically charged particles interacting by means of exchange of photons and represents the quantum counterpart of classical electromagnetism giving a complete account of matter and light interaction.
